# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2021-boulder-shooting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The **1982 Wilkes-Barre shootings** was a spree shooting which occurred in the United States on September 25, 1982, carried out by **George Emil Banks**, a former Camp Hill prison guard.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks fatally shot 13 people in Wilkes-Barre and Jenkins Township, Pennsylvania.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The victims included seven children – five being his own – their mothers, their relatives, and one bystander.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks' attorneys argued for the insanity defense, but following a trial, Banks was convicted of 12 counts of first-degree murder and sentenced to death.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 29, 1990, the Pennsylvania State Legislature barred further use of the electric chair amid debate that electrocution was cruel and unusual punishment; it approved execution by lethal injection.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks's case was appealed and, on December 2, 2004, he received a stay of execution following a determination that he was incompetent for execution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On May 12, 2010, Banks was declared incompetent to be executed, following a competency hearing held the previous month.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 2, 2025, Banks died in prison at the age of 83.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The shooting remains the deadliest in the history of Pennsylvania.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On the night of September 24, 1982, Banks drank a large quantity of gin and took prescription drugs at his home on Schoolhouse Lane in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The next morning on September 25, 1982, he used an AR-15 semi-automatic rifle to kill eight people in his house, including three women in their 20s (all girlfriends and mothers of his children) and five children, four of them his.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks dressed in military fatigues and went outside, where he saw 22-year-old Jimmy Olsen and 24-year-old Ray Hall Jr, leaving a house across the street.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He shot them both, reportedly yelling that they "would not tell anyone about this" before firing.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He hit both men, fatally wounding Hall; Olsen survived.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks went to Heather Highlands mobile home park, where his former girlfriend Sharon Mazzillo and their son Kissamayu lived, of whom he had been trying to gain custody.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks forced his way in and shot Mazzillo.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He then shot and killed his sleeping son.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks killed Sharon's mother, who was trying to call the police, and Sharon's 7-year-old nephew, who was also in the home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Sharon was shot in the heart and the other three were shot in the head.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Sharon's brothers, whom Banks did not see, hid, one in a closet and one under his mother's bed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They called the police and identified Banks as the shooter.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] When police examined the victims at the mobile home park, they connected the incident to Olsen and Hall's shooting, which had been discovered at Schoolhouse Lane.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They next found Banks's victims in his house.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Police began to search for Banks, who abandoned his car and carjacked another vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After abandoning the stolen vehicle, Banks stopped in an isolated grassy area to rest, and subsequently fell asleep.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After Banks awoke, he visited his mother's house (also in Wilkes-Barre.) He was said to have confessed his crimes to her.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] She drove him to the house of Jacob Whitt, a friend of Banks, where he sent her away and prepared for a standoff with police.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] A standoff between Banks and police began.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The police brought his mother to their base to talk with Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They tried various tactics to get the murderer to surrender, including having a false news report played over WILK radio saying that the children were alive and needed blood to survive.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The police tried other tactics to draw Banks out of the house.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Finally, Robert Brunson, a former co-worker of Banks, was able to talk him out after a 4-hour standoff.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On September 30, 1982, Banks was charged with eight counts of murder, attempted murder, aggravated assault, reckless endangerment, grand theft auto, armed robbery, and felonious theft.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Montanzima Banks (6) - Daughter of Clemens and Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Susan Yuhas (23) - Girlfriend of Banks, sister of Regina Clemens.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Boende Banks (4) - Son of Yuhas and Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Mauritania Banks (20 months) - Daughter of Yuhas and Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Dorothy Lyons (29) - Girlfriend of George Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Nancy Lyons (11) - Daughter of Dorothy Lyons.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Foraroude Banks (1) - Son of Dorothy Lyons and George Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] (24) - Bystander shot across from Banks' house on Schoolhouse Lane.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Kissmayu Banks (5) - Son of Sharon Mazzillo and George Banks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Scott Mazzillo (7) - Nephew of Sharon Mazzillo.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Alice Mazzillo (47) - Sharon Mazzillo's mother.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 1961 at 19, after being discharged from the Army, Banks and some accomplices robbed a tavern, shooting and injuring the unarmed owner.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was sentenced to six to fifteen years in prison, which was extended when he briefly escaped in 1964; however, he was granted parole in 1969, and his sentence was commuted by then Governor Milton Shapp in 1974.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After his release from prison, he married a black woman, Doris M.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The couple divorced in 1976, after which Banks exclusively dated white women.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] By September 1982, he had broken up with girlfriend Sharon Mazillo, who had lived with him at one time, and they were disputing custody of their young son.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was living together with three girlfriends and their four children he had fathered; one also had another man's daughter living with them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks was hired as a correctional officer at Camp Hill, Pennsylvania, in 1980, despite his criminal record that included the eight years served in prison after the 1961 armed robbery.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 1982, shortly before his murder spree, Banks told coworkers that he believed a race war was imminent and that he wished to save the five children he had fathered with four different white girlfriends from the horrors of racism he had supposedly suffered as a child.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On September 6, he locked himself in a guard tower with a shotgun and threatened to commit suicide—as a result, he was placed on extended leave and ordered to undergo mental-health examination at a Harrisburg-area hospital.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On June 6, 1983, Banks' trial began at the Luzerne County Courthouse in Wilkes Barre, Pennsylvania.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Albert Joseph Flora Jr. was appointed to be his defense attorney.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He said that he had only wounded some of the victims and police had killed them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Several scene witnesses, Banks family members, and Olsen testified.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Olsen identified Banks as the person who shot him and left him for dead.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Closing arguments took place on June 21, 1983.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks' attorney argued that he was insane, but the jury found Banks guilty of 12 counts of first-degree murder, one count of third-degree murder, attempted murder, aggravated assault, and one count each of robbery, theft, and endangering the life of another person.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On June 22, 1983, the jury recommended the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks was incarcerated in the maximum-security unit at Huntingdon until November 1985.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Supreme Court, but it refused to overturn his verdict.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was then sent to the Correctional Institute at Graterford, where he was housed in a contained housing unit.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] From 1987 to 2000, Banks' attorneys continued to appeal his case.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Supreme Court refused to hear his attorneys' argument that he lacked the mental competency to be executed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge twice signed a death warrant for Banks; however, both times federal appellate courts stayed his execution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2001, 2006, and 2008, the court held hearings about the mental state of Banks to determine if he could be executed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He exhibited delusional behavior that caused the court to rule him incompetent for execution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] During this period, various appeals were being heard by state and federal courts.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2010, another hearing was held on his competency; his attorney said his mental state had deteriorated significantly since 1982.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] A judge ruled that Banks was mentally incompetent for execution or to assist his attorneys in seeking clemency.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He would continue to be held in a restricted housing unit at Graterford Prison.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In September 2017, he was still on death row in Pennsylvania.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was later transferred to SCI-Phoenix in May 2018.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 2, 2025, Banks died at the age of 83 in his cell at SCI-Phoenix.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The coroner said in a statement that an autopsy was performed, and the cause of death was kidney cancer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] During appeals of his case, Banks was examined more than once in competency hearings by the court to determine if he was competent for execution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was found mentally incompetent on three occasions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2006, psychiatrists testified that he was "psychotic, delusional, and irrational." In May 2010, a Luzerne County Common Pleas judge held a new hearing and determined that Banks was mentally incompetent for execution or to assist his attorney in a clemency appeal.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In September 2017, he was held in a restricted housing unit at Graterford prison.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was relocated to SCI Phoenix following the 2018 closure of SCI Graterford.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The **Palm Sunday massacre** was a mass shooting which took place on April 15, 1984, in Brooklyn, New York, United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] It resulted in the deaths of ten people: two women, two teenage girls, and six children.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] All of the victims were shot, with a total of 19 bullets fired from two handguns at close range, most in the head, and were found in relaxed poses sitting in couches and chairs, suggesting that they had been taken by surprise.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] There were no signs of drugs or robbery at the home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In 1985, Christopher Thomas was convicted on ten counts of manslaughter, but was cleared of murder charges.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The jury had convicted him of intentional murder, but the charges were reduced due to "extreme emotional disturbance" and Thomas being high on drugs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Prosecutors said the motive was jealousy, claiming Thomas suspected his wife of having an affair with the home's owner, a convicted cocaine dealer named Enrique Bermudez.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Thomas's wife testified her husband was "enraged" over finding her at the Bermudez residence without him and set fire to his and her shared residence when she told him she was leaving him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Bermudez claimed Thomas had once asked Bermudez to have sex with Thomas's wife, but Bermudez declined.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Other witnesses testified they had seen Thomas “looking bizarre” in or near the residence earlier on the day of the murders.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Bermudez confirmed this, saying Thomas had visited him that morning asking for drugs and cash.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] When Bermudez asked about some $9,000 Thomas already owed him, Thomas reportedly promised a surprise.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Thomas was sentenced to from 83 to 250 years, but due to state law was expected to spend no more than 50 years in prison.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] He ended up serving just over 32 years before being released in 2018, having served two thirds of the maximum fifty years allowed by New York State.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The sole survivor, an infant girl, was raised by her grandmother.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Joanne Jaffe, at the time a "beat cop" and by 2014 the highest ranking female officer in the New York City Police Department, was assigned to the infant girl, and stayed in contact with her as she grew up.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The girl lived with Jaffe starting at age 14.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In 2014, after the death of the girl's grandmother, Jaffe adopted her at the age of 31.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In January 2018, Thomas was paroled from prison, after being incarcerated for nearly 34 years.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] On April 3, 2009, a mass shooting occurred at the American Civic Association immigration center in Binghamton, New York.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] EDT, Jiverly Wong (also known as Jiverly Voong) entered the facility and killed thirteen people and wounded four others before committing suicide.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] It is the deadliest mass shooting by a lone gunman in the state of New York.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] EDT, Jiverly Wong barricaded the rear door of the Binghamton American Civic Association building with a vehicle registered in his father's name.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] He was described as wearing a bullet-proof vest, a bright green nylon jacket, and dark-rimmed glasses.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong entered through the front door, firing a number of bullets at people in his path.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] At 10:31 a.m., Broome County Communications received several 911 calls, and the first police were dispatched to the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Two of the Civic Association's receptionists were among the first victims shot.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] While one of the receptionists was reported to have been shot through the head and killed, the second, shot in the stomach, feigned death and, when the gunman moved on, took cover under a desk and called 911.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The receptionist's call was taken by 911 staff at 10:38 a.m., when police had already arrived at the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The wounded receptionist, 61-year-old Shirley DeLucia, remained on the line for 39 minutes, despite her gunshot wound, and relayed information until she was rescued.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] She later recounted that the gunman had opened fire without saying anything.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The gunman entered a classroom just off the main reception areas, where an ESL class was being given to students.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Out of the 16 people in the room, Wong shot 13 of them, including the professor.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] He then took dozens of other students hostage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Police arrived within minutes of the first 911 calls.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Hearing the alarms, Wong committed suicide by shooting himself at 10:33 a.m., less than two minutes after he first opened fire.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In all, Wong fired 99 rounds: 88 from a 9mm Beretta and 11 from a .45-caliber Beretta.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Police remained at the perimeter of the property, having locked down nearby Binghamton High School and a number of streets in the area.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] At one point, not knowing if the gunman was alive or dead, police summoned Broome Community College Assistant Professor Tuong Hung Nguyen, who is fluent in Vietnamese, to help communicate with Wong in the event of contact.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] SWAT members entered the Civic Center building and began clearing it at 11:13 a.m., 43 minutes after the first call to the police at 10:30 a.m., and 40 minutes after patrol officers first arrived on the scene at 10:33 a.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] At the time of their entry, they had not yet confirmed that Wong had committed suicide, and they proceeded with caution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] At approximately noon, ten people left the building, with another ten following approximately forty minutes later.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Some of the hostages had escaped to a basement, while more than a dozen remained hidden in a closet.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Thanh Huynh, a high school teacher of Vietnamese background, was asked to interpret so the Vietnamese survivors could be interviewed by the police.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong was found dead from a self-inflicted gunshot wound, in the first-floor classroom with his victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Items found on Wong's body included a hunting knife in the waistband of his pants; a bag of ammunition which was tied around his neck; and two semi-automatic pistols (a .45-caliber Beretta Px4 Storm and a 9mm Beretta 92FS Vertec Inox matching the serial numbers on his New York State pistol license).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Also found at the scene were a number of loaded magazines, at least two empty magazines with a 30-round capacity each, and a firearm laser sight.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] By 2:33 p.m., SWAT had completed the clearing of the building, and all those inside had been evacuated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong killed 13 people and critically wounded four.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] An account of each of the victims was published in *The New York Times* on April 6, 2009.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Eight were residents of Binghamton, three were from Endicott, one was from Endwell, and one was from Greene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The injured were treated for gunshot wounds at Wilson Medical Center in Johnson City and Our Lady of Lourdes Memorial Hospital in Binghamton.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong was born in South Vietnam as the second of four children into a Buddhist ethnic Chinese family, which the online US-based news blog *Bolsavik* identified as Chinese Nùng, based on the spelling of their surname.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] His father was a captain in the South Vietnamese Army.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong and his parents, Henry Voong and Mui Thong, emigrated from Saigon in June 1990, arriving in the United States the following month, where their surname was romanized as Voong.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Initially living in Binghamton with his parents and siblings, within a year, he moved out of the family home to a separate apartment in Binghamton, finding employment at Felchar Manufacturer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] A few months later, he moved to the Los Angeles area in 1991.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Between the 1990s and 2000s, Wong regularly traveled back and forth between Los Angeles and New York, though without visiting his family.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In California, Wong was arrested twice, once in 1991 for an unknown charge and a second time in 1992, this time leading to a conviction on a misdemeanor charge of fraud for forgery.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong became a naturalized American citizen in November 1995, changing his name from Linh Phat Voong to Jiverly Antares Wong shortly after, though he also used the name Jiverly Voong as an alias, retaining an identity card with this spelling.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In February and June 1997, he registered guns in Broome County, New York, where he became a member of two shooting clubs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Shortly after, he acquired another gun license in California.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In August 1998, while living in Johnson City, Wong filed a report with police, claiming someone had broken into his apartment through a damaged window.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] It was determined that the window pane may have popped out of its frame due to wear and as there were no other signs of a break-in, the matter was not further investigated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Two days later, Wong was fined $20 for driving an uninspected vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In 1999, New York State Police received a report by an informant that Wong was planning a bank robbery, which also alleged that he had a crack cocaine addiction and owned several handguns.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong was not further investigated and no robbery occurred.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong left the U.S. the same year for Tokyo, only to re-enter on December 25, 1999.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Two days before his return, Wong married Xiu Ping Jiang.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In 2000, Wong moved to Inglewood, California, residing on Century Boulevard between September 2000 and September 2007, being noted once by police for a fender bender traffic incident.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong worked for almost seven years as a delivery man for Kikka Sushi, a catering company located in Los Angeles.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In May 2005, Wong and his wife separated, with her filing for divorce in July 2005, which was granted in July 2006, citing irreconcilable differences.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong failed to show up to work one day in July 2007.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The same year, he moved back with his parents, now living in Union, telling his father he had been fired from his job as a truck driver.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] However, co-workers stated that Wong had quit the job without any reason.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Later, he called the company to get a copy of his W-2 earnings statement in 2008, asking that it be forwarded to a New York state address.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong worked at a local Shop-Vac vacuum cleaner plant until it closed in November 2008.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] By that point, Wong had again started visiting shooting ranges in Binghamton.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] After losing his job, Wong had regular appointments at Binghamton's employment center to receive his Trade Adjustment Assistance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] On his first visit in November 2008, he left the center in anger after the receptionist, intending to call a translator, asked him if he was Chinese or Japanese.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] His attendance was intermittent, and he stopped coming altogether in March 2009.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] He shot the students and teacher in the classroom where he had formerly attended sessions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Several sources suggested possible motives for Wong's attack, including feelings of being "degraded and disrespected" for his poor English language skills, depression over losing his job, and difficulty in finding work in New York.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Neighbors additionally suspected that Wong had an addiction to drugs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Several days after the shooting, an envelope was received by the Syracuse, New York, TV station News 10 Now dated March 18, 2009, and postmarked April 3, 2009, the day of the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The three stamps used for the postage were a Liberty Bell and two Purple Hearts.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The package contained a two-page handwritten letter; photos of Wong, holding guns while smiling; a gun permit; and Wong's driver's license.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Of the letter itself, most of its content was a rambling, paranoid accusation of perceived police misconduct and persecution of him, especially through "secret" visits to his residences.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The letter also complained about the New York State Department of Labor, claiming that they had failed to provide him with unemployment benefits for a month.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] At the end of the letter, Wong stated that he "must [get] at least two people with me go to return to the dust of earth [*sic*]", blaming police for his actions, writing "Cop bring about this shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The shooting was the deadliest mass shooting in Binghamton's history, although not the deadliest mass casualty incident overall in the city, which was the 1913 Binghamton Factory fire with 31 deaths.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The Binghamton shooting was the eighth high-profile mass shooting in the United States since March 10, 2009, all having occurred within less than a month, leading to a renewed debate about gun control measures that members of the Democratic Party had previously proposed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Former Rochester County prosecutor Jeffrey Chamberlain commented that Wong "fell through the cracks" while Binghamton Police Chief Zikuski stated that there was "no merit" to reviewing Wong's gun permits after the alleged robbery tip-off in 1999.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] There was criticism against the Binghamton police department for waiting 45 minutes while on-site before entering the premises.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The *New York Daily News* wrote in the department's defense that autopsies determined all fatalities had sustained injuries which resulted in death before the emergency response.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Although early reports suggested Wong had recently lost his job at a local IBM plant in nearby Endicott, New York, IBM said they had no records showing Wong had ever worked for the company.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Press TV noted that Pakistani Taliban leader Baitullah Mehsud claimed responsibility for the shooting, saying, "They were my men.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] I gave them orders in reaction to US drone attacks." However, a spokesman for the Federal Bureau of Investigation discounted the claim as inconsistent with their evidence that Wong was the lone gunman.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] President Barack Obama referred to the shooting as "senseless violence" and offered sympathy to the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] New York Governor David Paterson ordered state flags to be flown at half staff on April 8, 2009.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Wong's parents, Henry Voong and Mui Thong of Johnson City, New York, issued a statement apologizing for their son's actions, expressing their shared grief and asking for forgiveness from the victims' families.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Following the publication of Wong's personal details, reporters attempted to find Wong's ex-wife, Xiu Ping Jiang, for comment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] A Chinese woman with the same name, who had married a Vietnamese man in Des Moines, Iowa, was identified in an immigration jail in Glades County, Florida, but a background check determined her to be a different person.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] However, information about this Xiu Ping Jiang's immigration process generated sympathy about unfair treatment following coverage by *The New York Times* in September 2009.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Instead, she is a kind of Internet-era doppelganger, lost in one of the dark places of immigration law, where the only life at stake may be her own".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] She was subsequently granted a second process under consideration of her mental health issues, receiving asylum in 2010.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The events of Xiu Ping Jiang's immigration case became the basis of Lisa Ko's 2017 novel *The Leavers*.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In 2010, ahead of the one-year anniversary, a memorial was officially announced to commemorate the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In spring 2013, the ACA Memorial Park was constructed, funded by $200,000 paid by public donations and the victims' families.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] The center of the park features thirteen memorial plaques and an equal number of dove statues.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] In 2019, Binghamton University planned to build a mosaic at the entrance of the ACA center as part of a PwC honors program, which was suspended due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but construction took place in April 2021.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-binghamton-shooting] Yearly memorial services for the shooting's victims are held in the park.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On November 5, 2009, a mass shooting took place at Fort Hood near Killeen, Texas, United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army major and psychiatrist, fatally shot 13 people and injured more than 30 others.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] It was the deadliest mass shooting on an American military base and the deadliest terrorist attack in the United States since the September 11 attacks until it was surpassed by the San Bernardino attack in 2015.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan was shot and as a result paralyzed from the waist down.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was arraigned by a military court in 2011 and was charged with 13 counts of premeditated murder and 32 counts of attempted murder under the Uniform Code of Military Justice.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] At his court-martial in 2013, Hasan was found guilty on all counts and sentenced to death.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The failure to prevent the shooting led the Defense Department and the FBI to commission investigations, and Congress to hold hearings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The U.S. government declined requests from survivors and family members of the slain to categorize the Fort Hood shooting as an act of terrorism, or motivated by militant Islamic religious convictions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In November 2011, a group of survivors and family members filed a lawsuit against the government for negligence in preventing the attack, and to force the government to classify the shooting as terrorism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Pentagon argued that charging Hasan with terrorism was not possible within the military justice system and that such action could harm the military prosecutors' ability to sustain a guilty verdict against Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to pretrial testimony, Hasan entered the Guns Galore store in Killeen on July 31, 2009, and purchased the FN Five-seven semi-automatic pistol that he would use in the attack at Fort Hood.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to Army Specialist William Gilbert, a regular customer at the store, Hasan entered the store and asked for "the most technologically advanced weapon on the market and the one with the highest standard magazine capacity".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan was allegedly asked how he intended to use the weapon, but simply repeated that he wanted the most advanced handgun with the largest magazine capacity.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The three people with Hasan—Gilbert, the store manager, and an employee—all recommended the FN Five-seven pistol.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] As Gilbert owned one of the pistols, he spent an hour describing its operation to Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan left the store, saying he needed to research the weapon.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He returned to purchase the gun the next day, and visited the store once a week to buy extra magazines, along with over 3,000 rounds of 5.7×28mm SS192 and SS197SR ammunition total.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In the weeks prior to the attack, Hasan visited an outdoor shooting range in Florence, where he allegedly became adept at hitting silhouette targets at distances of up to 100 yards.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] At approximately 1:34 p.m. local time, November 5, 2009, Hasan entered the Soldier Readiness Processing Center, where personnel receive routine medical treatment immediately prior to and on return from deployment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was preparing to deploy to Afghanistan with his unit and had been to the Center several times before.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was armed with the FN Five-seven pistol, which he had fitted with two Lasermax laser sights: one red, and one green.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A Smith & Wesson .357 Magnum revolver (an older model) was later found on Hasan's person, but he did not use it to shoot any of the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] After entering the building, Hasan went to the first desk to the right of the North doors and asked to see Major Parrish.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Parrish worked in the building (and had been assisting Hasan in his deployment preparations).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The worker went down the hall to get Parrish.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to eyewitnesses, Hasan then went around behind the desk and bowed his head for several seconds, before he suddenly stood up, shouted "*Allahu Akbar!* " and opened fire.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Witnesses said Hasan initially "sprayed bullets at soldiers in a fanlike motion" before taking aim at individual soldiers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Eyewitness SGT Michael Davis said: "The rate of fire was pretty much constant shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army Reserve Captain John Gaffaney tried to stop Hasan by charging him, but was mortally wounded before reaching him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Civilian physician assistant Michael Cahill also tried to charge Hasan with a chair, but was shot and killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army Reserve Specialist Logan Burnett tried to stop Hasan by throwing a folding table at him, but he was shot in the left hip, fell down, and crawled to a nearby cubicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to testimony from witnesses, Hasan passed up several opportunities to shoot civilians, and instead targeted soldiers in uniform, who – in accordance with military policy – were not carrying personal firearms.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] At one point, Hasan reportedly approached a group of five civilians hiding under a desk.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He looked at them, swept the dot of his pistol's laser sight over one of the men's faces, and turned away without firing.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] While this was going on, an Army Specialist broke a window in the back of the building where Parrish worked.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Two soldiers and Parrish exited the building through the broken window on the east side of the building and escaped to the parking lot, though one soldier severely cut his hand on broken glass.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] All of this happened as Hasan was still roaming the building and shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Base civilian police Sergeant Kimberly Munley, who had rushed to the scene in her patrol car, encountered Hasan in the area outside the Soldier Readiness Processing Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan fired at Munley, who exchanged shots with him using her 9mm M9 pistol.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Munley's hand was hit by shrapnel when one of Hasan's bullets struck a nearby rain gutter, and then two bullets struck Munley: the first bullet hit her thigh, and the second hit her knee.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] As she began to fall from the first bullet, the second bullet struck her femur, shattering it and knocking her to the ground.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan walked up to Munley and kicked her pistol out of reach.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] As the shooting continued outside, nurses and medics entered the building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] An unidentified soldier secured the south double doors with his ACU belt and rushed to help the wounded.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to the responding nurses, there was so much blood covering the floor inside the building that they were unable to maintain balance, and had difficulty reaching the wounded to help them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In the area outside the building, Hasan continued to shoot at fleeing soldiers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Herman Toro, Director of the Soldier Readiness Processing Site, arrived at this time.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan had gone around the building and was out of sight, but still shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Toro and another site worker rushed to assist Lieutenant Colonel Juanita Warman, who was down on the ground north of the medical building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] They both took her by the arms and tried to carry her to safety when Hasan returned and aimed his red laser across Toro's chest, but did not fire.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Toro took cover behind an electrical box and saw civilian police Sergeant Mark Todd arrive and shout commands at Hasan to surrender.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Todd said: "Then he turned and fired a couple of rounds at me.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] I didn't hear him say a word, he just turned and fired." The two exchanged shots, Hasan emptying his pistol in the process.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He stopped, turned, and reached into his pocket for a new magazine before being felled by five shots from Todd.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Todd then ran over to Hasan, kicked the pistol out of his hand, and put handcuffs on him as he fell unconscious.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] LTC Tom Eberhart, Deputy Director of Human Resources, Fort Hood, arrived and entered the Medical Building to help.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He had to step over bodies to enter the building's north entrance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He assisted another soldier in performing CPR on one of the wounded soldiers at the building's waiting area.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Folding chairs were scattered all around.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He noticed a soldier outside the south doors of the building and went to help, removing the belt from the door.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The downed soldier was Staff Sergeant Alonzo Lunsford, a medical assistant from the building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He had two wounds in the abdomen and a wound to the scalp.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was unconscious and LTC Eberhart went back into the building to retrieve a folding table.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Other soldiers assisted in getting SSG Lunsford onto the table and around the building to the triage area.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] An investigator later testified that 146 spent shell casings were recovered inside the building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Another 68 casings were collected outside, for a total of 214 rounds fired by the attacker and responding police officers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A medic who treated Hasan said his pockets were full of pistol magazines.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] When the shooting ended, he was still carrying 177 rounds of unfired ammunition in his pockets, contained in both 20- and 30-round magazines.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The incident, which lasted about 10 minutes, resulted in 13 killed—12 soldiers and one civilian; 11 died at the scene, and two died later in a hospital; and 30 people wounded.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Initially, officials thought three soldiers were involved in the shooting; two other soldiers were detained, but subsequently released.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Fort Hood website posted a notice indicating that the shooting was not a drill.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Immediately after the shooting, the base and surrounding areas were locked down by military police and U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army Criminal Investigation Command (CID) until around 7 pm local time.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In addition, Texas Rangers, Texas DPS troopers, deputies from the Bell County Sheriff's Office, and FBI agents from Austin and Waco were dispatched to the base.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] President Barack Obama was briefed on the incident and later made a statement about the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On November 5, 2010, one year later, 52 individuals received awards for their actions in the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Soldier's Medal was awarded posthumously to Captain John Gaffaney, who died trying to charge the shooter; fifty other medals were presented to other responders, including seven others who were awarded the Soldier's Medal.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Secretary of the Army Award for Valor was awarded to police officers Kimberly Munley and Mark Todd, for the roles they played in stopping the shooter.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On May 23, 2011, the Army Award for Valor was posthumously awarded to the civilian physician assistant Michael Cahill, who died trying to charge the shooter with a chair.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In May 2012, Senator Joe Lieberman and Representative Peter T.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] King proposed legislation that would make the victims of the shooting eligible for the Purple Heart.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In the 113th Congress, Representative John Carter introduced legislation to change the shooting designation from "workplace violence" to "combat related" which would make the victims of the shooting eligible to receive full benefits and the Purple Heart.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In July 2014, a memorial for those killed during the attack began to be built in Killeen.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The dedication ceremony for the memorial was held in March 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Department of Defense issued a press release, in which Secretary of the Army John M.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] McHugh announced that he was approving the awarding of the Purple Heart and its civilian counterpart, the Secretary of Defense Medal for the Defense of Freedom, to victims of the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] This is a result of Congress expanding the eligibility requirement under a provision of the National Defense Authorization Act of 2015.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On April 10, 2015, nearly 50 awards were handed out to dozens of survivors.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In October 2018, the Program on Extremism at George Washington University published a case study about the radicalization of Nidal Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The report is based on previously unpublished as well as new sources including primary source documents, discussions with those close to Hasan, and interviews with Hasan himself.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The paper concludes that his faith was fundamental to the development of his worldview and his pathway towards radicalization, and that his radicalization followed a linear pathway.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Thirteen people - 12 soldiers and 1 civilian - were killed in the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Over thirty people were wounded; some from gunshots, others from falls or other injuries incurred during the incident, and many suffered psychological trauma or shock.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Army, press, and investigative bodies have reported several numbers for the total number of injured, without indicating what sorts of injuries they were counting, nor how: 29; 30; 31; 32; 38; and 42.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan, the gunman, was taken to Scott and White Memorial Hospital, a trauma center in Temple, Texas, and later moved to Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] As a result of being shot, he is now paraplegic.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was later held at the Bell County jail in Belton, Texas.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Ten of the injured were also treated at Scott and White.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Seven wounded victims were taken to Metroplex Adventist Hospital in Killeen.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On November 20, 2009, it was announced that eight of the wounded service members would deploy overseas.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] During his court-martial on August 6, 2013 before a panel of 13 officers, Major Nidal Malik Hasan declared that he was the shooter.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan is unmarried and was described as socially isolated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Born in the United States, Hasan is a practicing Muslim who, according to one of his cousins, became more devout after the deaths of his parents in 1998 and 2001.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] His cousin did not recall him ever expressing radical or anti-American views.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Another cousin, Nader Hasan, a lawyer in Virginia, said that Nidal Hasan's opinion turned against the United States after he heard stories from his patients, who had returned from fighting in Afghanistan and Iraq.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Because of what Hasan said was discrimination and his deepening anguish about serving in a military that fought against Muslims, he told some members of his family that he wanted to leave the military.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] From 2003 to 2009, Hasan was stationed at Walter Reed Medical Center for his internship and residency; he also had a two-year fellowship at USUHS completed in 2009.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to National Public Radio (NPR) and the Associated Press (AP), officials at Walter Reed Medical Center repeatedly expressed concern about Hasan's behavior during the entire six years he was there.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan's supervisors gave him poor evaluations and warned him that he was doing substandard work.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In early 2008 (and on later occasions), several key officials met to discuss what to do about Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to NPR, fellow students and faculty were "deeply troubled" by Hasan's behavior, which they described as "disconnected", "aloof", "paranoid", "belligerent" and "schizoid".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] NPR, *The Washington Post*, and the Associated Press all reported on a presentation by Hasan that was originally planned as a medical lecture for other psychiatrists but instead was about Islam.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In that lecture, Hasan said, according to the Quran, non-believers would be sent to hell, decapitated, set on fire, and have burning oil poured down their throats.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A Muslim psychiatrist in the audience raised his hand, and challenged Hasan's claims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] According to the Associated Press, Hasan's lecture also "justified suicide bombings".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In the summer of 2009, after completion of his programs, he was transferred to Fort Hood.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] At Fort Hood, Hasan rented an apartment away from other officers, in a somewhat rundown area.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Two days before the shooting, Hasan gave away furniture from his home, saying he was going to be deployed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He also handed out copies of the Quran, along with his business cards, which gave a Maryland phone number and read "Behavioral Heatlh [*sic*] – Mental Health – Life Skills | Nidal Hasan, MD, MPH | SoA(SWT) | Psychiatrist".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The cards did not reflect his military rank.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In May 2001, Hasan attended the funeral of his mother, held at the Dar Al-Hijrah mosque in Falls Church, Virginia, which has 3,000 members.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He may also have occasionally prayed there but, for a period of ten years, he prayed several times a week at the Muslim Community Center in Silver Spring, Maryland, closer to where he lived and worked.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He was regularly seen at the Muslim Community Center by the imam and other members.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] His attendance at the Falls Church mosque was in the same period as that of Nawaf al-Hazmi and Hani Hanjour, two of the hijackers in the September 11 attacks, who went there from April 2001 to later in the summer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A law enforcement official said that the FBI would probably look into whether Hasan associated with the hijackers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A review of Hasan's computer and his e-mail accounts revealed he had visited radical Islamist websites, a senior law enforcement official said.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hasan expressed admiration for the teachings of Anwar al-Awlaki, the imam at the Dar al-Hijrah mosque in Falls Church, Virginia between 2000 and 2002.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Awlaki had been the subject of several FBI investigations, and had helped hijackers al-Hazmi and Hanjour settle, and provided spiritual guidance to them when they met him at the San Diego mosque, and after they drove to the east coast.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Considered moderate then, Al-Awlaki appeared to become radicalized after 2006 and was under surveillance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] After Hasan wrote nearly 20 e-mails to him between December 2008 and June 2009, Hasan was investigated by the FBI.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The fact that Hasan had "certain communications" with the subject of a Joint Terrorism Task Force investigation was revealed in an FBI press release made on November 11, 2009, and reporting by the media immediately revealed that the subject was Awlaki and the communications were e-mails.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In one, Hasan wrote: "I can't wait to join you" in the afterlife.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Tony Shaffer, a military analyst at the Center for Advanced Defense Studies, suggested that Hasan was "either offering himself up or [had] already crossed that line in his own mind".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army employees were informed of the contacts at the time, but they believed that the e-mails were consistent with Hasan's professional mental health research about Muslims in the armed services, as part of his master's work in disaster and preventive psychiatry.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A DC-based joint terrorism task force operating under the FBI was notified, and the information reviewed by one of its Defense Criminal Investigative Service (DCIS) employees, who concluded there was not sufficient information for a larger investigation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Senior officers at the Department of Defense stated they were not notified of such investigations before the shootings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Immediately after the shooting, analysts and public officials openly debated Hasan's motive and preceding psychological state.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison, one of the first officials to comment on Hasan's background, told reporters that Hasan was upset about his pending deployment to Afghanistan on November 28.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Noel Hamad, Hasan's aunt, said that the family was not aware he was being sent to Afghanistan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Citing anonymous sources, ABC News reported on November 16, 2009, that investigators suspect that the shootings were triggered by superiors' refusal to process Hasan's requests that some of his patients be prosecuted for war crimes based on statements they made during psychiatric sessions with him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Fellow psychiatrists complained to superiors that Hasan's actions violated doctor-patient confidentiality.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Duane Reasoner, a convert to Islam whom Hasan was mentoring in the religion, said the psychiatrist did not want to be deployed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] "'He said Muslims shouldn't be in the U.S. military, because obviously Muslims shouldn't kill Muslims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Senator Joe Lieberman called for a probe by the Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs, which he chaired.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Lieberman said "it's premature to reach conclusions about what motivated Hasan ...
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] I think it's very important to let the Army and the FBI go forward with this investigation before we reach any conclusions." Two weeks later, when opening his committee's hearings, Lieberman labeled the shooting "the most destructive terrorist attack on America since September 11, 2001".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] An analyst of terror investigations, Carl Tobias, opined that the attack did not fit the profile of terrorism, and was more similar to the Virginia Tech massacre, committed by a student believed to be severely mentally ill.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Michael Scheuer, the retired former head of the Bin Laden Issue Station, and former U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Attorney General Michael Mukasey have called the event a terrorist attack, as has the terrorism expert Walid Phares.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Retired General Barry McCaffrey said on *Anderson Cooper 360°* that "it's starting to appear as if this was a domestic terrorist attack on fellow soldiers by a major in the Army who we educated for six years while he was giving off these vibes of disloyalty to his own force".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Some of Hasan's former colleagues have said he performed substandard work and occasionally unnerved them by expressing fervent Islamic views and deep opposition to the U.S.-led wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Others were more concerned about his apparent mental instability and paranoid behaviors.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Throughout his years at Walter Reed, heads of departments had regularly discussed his mental state, as they were "deeply concerned" about his behavior.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Brian Levin of the Center for the Study of Hate and Extremism wrote that the case sits at the crossroads of crime, terrorism and mental distress.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He compared the possible role of religion to the beliefs of Scott Roeder, a Christian who murdered Dr.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Such offenders "often self-radicalize from a volatile mix of personal distress, psychological issues, and an ideology that can be sculpted to justify and explain their anti-social leanings".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] At his trial in June 2013, Hasan declared his motive as wanting to defend the lives of the Taliban leadership in Afghanistan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Army prosecutors said that he sought to align himself with Islamic extremists.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In August 2013, Fox News released documents from Hasan in which he explained his motives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Most of the documents included the acronym "SoA", which is considered shorthand for "Soldier of Allah".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In one document, Hasan wrote that he was required to renounce any oaths that required him to defend any man-made constitution over the commandments mandated in Islam.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In another document, he wrote "I invite the world to read the book of All-Mighty Allah and decide for themselves if it is the truth from their Lord.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In another document, Hasan wrote that there is a fundamental and irreconcilable conflict between American democracy and Islamic governance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He further explained that separation of Church and State is an unacceptable attempt to get along with unbelievers, because "Islam was brought to prevail over other religions" and not to be equal with or subservient to them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Many have characterized the attack as terrorism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A group of soldiers and families have sought to have the defense secretary designate the shooting a "terrorist attack;" this would provide them with benefits equal to injuries in combat.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The FBI found no evidence to indicate Hasan had any co-conspirators or was part of a broader terrorist plot, classifying him as a homegrown violent extremist.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Conversely, the Defense Department currently classifies Hasan's attack as an act of workplace violence and would not make further statements until the court martial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] President's initial response to the attack came during a scheduled speech at the Tribal Nations Conference for America's 564 federally recognized Native American tribes.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Later, the President delivered the memorial eulogy for the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Reaction to his memorial speech was largely positive, with some deeming it one of his best.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The speech was criticized by a reporter from *The Wall Street Journal*, who found the speech largely absent of emotion, while *National Review* columnist Andrew C.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] McCarthy criticized Obama for refusing to acknowledge Islamic terrorism as having a role in the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On December 6, 2015, in his speech addressing terrorism, Obama included the Fort Hood shooting among Islamic inspired terrorist incidents.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Retired Army colonel Terry Lee, who had worked with Hasan, said the psychiatrist expressed the hope that Obama would withdraw U.S. troops from Iraq and Afghanistan, and argued with military colleagues who supported the wars.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Homeland Security Secretary Janet Napolitano stated "we object to—and do not believe—that anti-Muslim sentiment should emanate from this ...
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] This was an individual who does not, obviously, represent the Muslim faith." Chief of Staff Gen.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Casey, Jr. said "I'm concerned that this increased speculation could cause a backlash against some of our Muslim soldiers ...
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Our diversity, not only in our Army, but in our country, is a strength.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In January 2010, a senior Obama administration official, who declined to be named, referred to the shooting as "an act of terrorism".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] However, other administration officials did not refer to the shootings as a terrorist event.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Several people, including Senator Joe Lieberman and General Barry McCaffrey, have called the event a terrorist attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The United States Department of Defense and federal law enforcement agencies had classified the shootings as an act of workplace violence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In November 2011, a group of survivors and family members filed a lawsuit against the government for negligence in preventing the attack, and to force the government to classify the shootings as terrorism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Victims of the shooting were denied Purple Hearts as well as associate benefits.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In 2013, during the 113th United States Congress, Representative Carter submitted the Honoring the Fort Hood Heroes Act for consideration.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In 2015, a similar bill was introduced in the legislature of Texas, to award the Texas Purple Heart Medal to the shooting victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The National Defense Authorization Act 2015 authorizes the Department of Defense to award Purple Heart Medals to those wounded during the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The award was previously denied due to the categorization of the event as "workplace violence".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The law requires that the Department of Defense to define the event as an "international terrorist attack".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] In February 2015, the Department of the Army approved awarding of the Purple Heart to those injured by Hasan during the shooting, providing those injured with a higher degree of services from Veterans Affairs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Army presented the Purple Hearts on April 10, 2015.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Following the awarding benefits for those wounded in hostile-fire were extended to the Purple Heart recipients, and it was announced that those killed and injured during the 2009 Little Rock recruiting office shooting would also receive the Purple Heart.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Veterans groups across the United States expressed condolences for victims of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] American Legion National Commander Clarence E.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Hill stated, "The American Legion extends condolences to the victims and the families of those affected by the shootings at Fort Hood." Veterans of Foreign Wars National Commander Thomas J.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Tradewell Sr. states, "The entire military family is grieving right now.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] I just want them to know they do not grieve alone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Army places strict restrictions on personal firearms carried onto Fort Hood and other bases.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Military weapons are used only for training or by base security.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Personal weapons brought on base are required to be secured at all times and must be registered with the provost marshal.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Specialist Jerry Richard, a soldier working at the Readiness Center, said he felt this policy left the soldiers vulnerable to violent assaults: "Overseas you are ready for it.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] But here you can't even defend yourself." Jacob Sullum, an opponent of gun control, described the base as a "gun-free zone".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] A spokeswoman for the Hasan family said that the actions of their cousin were "despicable and deplorable", and did not reflect how they were raised.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] The Council on American-Islamic Relations (CAIR) condemned the shooting and noted that it was not in keeping with Muslim teachings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] Soon after the attack, Anwar al-Awlaki posted praise for Hasan for the shooting on his website.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] He wrote, "Nidal Hasan is a hero, the fact that fighting against the U.S. army is an Islamic duty today cannot be disputed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] (Note: The US investigation found no evidence that ties Hasan to al-Qaeda.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On April 6, 2010, *The New York Times* reported that President Obama had authorized the targeted killing of al-Awlaki, who had been hunted by the Yemen government since going into hiding.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p01] On September 30, 2011, two Predator drones fired missiles at a vehicle with al-Awlaki aboard, killing him and Samir Khan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The criminal investigation was conducted jointly by the FBI, the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Army Criminal Investigation Command, and the Texas Rangers Division.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] As a member of the military, Hasan is subject to the jurisdiction of the Uniform Code of Military Justice (military law).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He was initially represented by Belton, Texas-based John P.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Galligan, a criminal defense attorney and retired US Army Colonel.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan regained consciousness on November 9, but refused to talk to investigators.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The investigative officer in charge of his article 32 hearing was Colonel James L.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Pohl, who had previously led the investigation into the Abu Ghraib abuses, and is the Chief Presiding Officer of the Guantanamo military commissions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On November 9, 2009, the FBI said that investigators believed Hasan had acted alone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] They disclosed that they had reviewed evidence which included conversations from 2008, with someone that an official identified as Anwar al-Awlaki, but that they did not find any evidence that Hasan had received orders or help from anyone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] According to a November 11 press release, after preliminary examination of Hasan's computers and internet activity, they had found no information to indicate he had any co-conspirators or was part of a broader terrorist plot, stressing the "early stages" of the review.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] They said no e-mail communications with outside facilitators or known terrorists were found.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Investigators were evaluating reports that, in May 2001, Hasan had attended a mosque in Virginia for the funeral of his mother, which was attended that spring and summer by two of the 9/11 hijackers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The imam was the American cleric Anwar al-Awlaki, then considered a moderate.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Awlaki has since been accused of aiding the 9/11 plot and since 2006–2007 has been identified as radicalized.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Investigators were trying to determine if al-Awlaki's teachings influenced Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan attended services at the Muslim Community Center in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Army officials operated "on the belief that he acted alone and had no help".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] No motive for the shootings was offered, but they believed Hasan had written an Internet posting that appeared to support suicide bombings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Lieberman opined that Hasan was under personal stress and may have turned to Islamic extremism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In pressing charges against Hasan, the Department of Defense and the DoJ agreed that Hasan would be prosecuted in a military court.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Observers noted this was consistent with investigators' concluding he had acted alone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On November 12 and December 2, respectively, Hasan was charged with 13 counts of premeditated murder and 32 counts of attempted murder by the Army.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Prosecutors did not file a count for the death of the Francheska Velez's three-month old fetus, although such a charge would have been possible under Article 119a of the Uniform Code of Military Justice.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] If civilian prosecutors indicted him for being part of a terrorist plot, it could have justified moving all or part of his case into federal criminal courts under U.S. anti-terrorism laws.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The military justice system rarely carries out capital punishment—and no executions have been carried out since 1961, though Ronald Gray came close to execution in 2008.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In January 2011, Hasan was judged sane for trial by a sanity board, composed of doctors and psychologists.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] This allowed a capital trial, and more information about his mental state at the time of the shootings was able to be introduced by the defense during the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He was formally arraigned on July 20, 2011.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He did not enter a plea, and the judge granted a request by Hasan's attorneys that a plea be entered later.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The judge set a court-martial date for March 5, 2012.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Later, the court-martial date was pushed back after Hasan switched lawyers, to provide them time to prepare his defense.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Having previously instructed Hasan to follow Army regulations and shave a beard he had grown, the judge, Colonel Gregory Gross, found him in contempt in July 2012 and fined him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] His court-martial was set to begin on August 20, 2012.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He was fined again for retaining his beard, and warned that he could be forcibly shaved prior to his court-martial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Gregory Gross declined any further delays to the August 20 court martial date.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan objected to being shaved against his will, and his attorney's appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan said having a beard was part of his religious belief.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On August 27, the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces ruled that the trial could continue but did not rule whether Hasan could be forcibly shaved, having previously rejected previous attempts by Hasan to receive "religious accommodation" from Army Regulation to wear his beard.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Gross ordered that Hasan be shaved after it was determined that the 1993 Religious Freedom Restoration Act did not apply to this case; however, it will not be enforced until his appeals are exhausted, further delaying the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On September 21, defense attorneys of Hasan filed two appeals with the Army Court of Criminal Appeals regarding his beard, postponing the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In mid-October, the Army Court of Criminal Appeals upheld Colonel Gross' decision that Hasan could be forcibly shaved.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan's attorneys filed an appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces seeking to overturn the lower court, and to have Gross removed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On December 4, 2012, the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces vacated Major Hasan's six convictions for contempt of court and removed the judge, Colonel Gregory Gross, from the case, stating he had not shown the requisite impartiality.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The Court of Appeals overturned an order to have Hasan's beard be forcibly shaven; it did not rule on whether Hasan's religious rights had been violated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The Court of Appeals additionally ruled that it was the military command's responsibility, not the military judge, to ensure Hasan met grooming standards.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The Army's Judge Advocate General appointed a new judge to replace Gross, Colonel Tara A.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The ruling was called "unusual" by Jeffrey Addicott of the Center for Terrorism Law at St.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Mary's University, and called "rare" by military defense attorney Frank Spinner.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In January 2013, Osborn was deliberating whether to remove the death penalty, due to the Defense attorney's claim that LTG Donald M.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Campbell, Jr. was not impartial when it was decided that Hasan would face the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On January 31, Osborn ruled that a capital murder trial was constitutional, based on a 1996 Supreme Court case regarding Dwight J.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Loving; Osborn additionally ruled that her court did not have jurisdiction regarding Hasan's beard, and it was a matter to take up with Hasan's chain of command.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Osborn scheduled the court-martial to start on May 29, 2013, with jury selection starting July 1.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On June 3, 2013, a military judge gave approval for Hasan to represent himself at his upcoming murder trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] His attorneys were to remain on the case but only if he asked for their help.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Jury selection started on June 5 and opening arguments took place on August 6.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Osborn ruled on June 14, 2013, that Hasan could not claim as a part of his defense that he was defending the Taliban.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] During an exclusive interview with Fox News, Hasan justified his actions during the Fort Hood shooting by claiming that the US military was at war with Islam.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] During the first day of the trial on August 6, Hasan—representing himself— admitted that he was the gunman during the Fort Hood shootings in 2009 and stated that the evidence would show that he was the shooter.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He also told the panel hearing that he had "switched sides" and regarded himself as a Mujahideen waging "jihad" against the United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] By August 7, disagreements between Hasan and his stand-by defense team led Judge Osborn to suspend the proceedings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan's defense attorneys were concerned that his defense strategy would lead to him receiving the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Since the prosecution had sought the death penalty, his defense team sought to prevent this.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Overall, the trial cost almost $5 million, with the largest expense being transportation, followed by expert witness fees.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On August 23, 2013, following a seven-hour deliberation, the jury convicted Hasan on all charges.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Five days later, a U.S. military court sentenced him to death for the shootings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] At the time of his sentencing, he became the sixth person on military death row.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The FBI noted that Hasan had first been brought to their attention in December 2008 by a Joint Terrorism Task Force (JTTF).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Communications between Hasan and al-Awlaki, and other similar communications, were reviewed and considered to be consistent with Hasan's professional research at the Walter Reed Medical Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In December 2009, FBI Director Robert Mueller appointed William H.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Webster, a former director of the FBI, to establish a commission to conduct an independent review of the FBI's handling of assessing the risk that Hasan posed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On January 15, 2010, the Department of Defense released the findings of its investigation, which found that the department was unprepared to defend against internal threats.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Secretary Robert Gates said that previous incidents had not drawn enough attention to workplace violence and "self-radicalization" within the military.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] He also suggested that some officials may be held responsible for not drawing attention to Hasan prior to the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The department report did not touch upon Hasan's motives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] James Corum, a retired Army Reserve Lieutenant Colonel and Dean at the Baltic Defence College in Estonia, called the Defense Department report "a travesty" for failing to mention Hasan's devotion to Islam and his radicalization.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Representative John Carter of Texas criticized the report, saying he felt the government was "afraid to be accused of profiling somebody".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The leaders of the investigation, former Secretary of the Army Togo D.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] West, Jr. and retired Admiral Vernon Clark, responded by saying their "concern is with actions and effects, not necessarily with motivations", and that they did not want to conflict with the criminal investigation on Hasan that was under way.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In February 2010, *The Boston Globe* obtained a confidential internal report detailing results of the Army's investigation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] According to the Globe, the report concluded that officers within the Army were aware of Hasan's tendencies toward radical Islam since 2005.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] It noted one incident in 2007 in which Hasan gave a classroom presentation titled, "Is the War on Terrorism a War on Islam: An Islamic Perspective".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The instructor reportedly interrupted Hasan, as he thought the psychiatrist was trying to justify terrorism, according to the *Globe*.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Hasan's superior officers took no action related to this incident, believing Hasan's comments were protected under the First Amendment and that having a Muslim psychiatrist contributed to diversity.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The report noted that Hasan's statements might have been grounds for removing him from service, as the First Amendment did not apply to soldiers in the same way as for civilians.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In July 2012, the Webster Commission's final report was submitted.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Webster made 18 recommendations to the FBI.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The report found issues in information sharing, failure to follow up on leads, computer technology issues, and failure of the FBI headquarters to coordinate two field offices working on leads related to Hasan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In August 2013, *Mother Jones* magazine described multiple intercepted e-mails from Hasan to Awlaki.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In one 2008 e-mail, Hasan asked Awlaki whether he considered those who died attacking their fellow soldiers "Shaheeds", or martyrs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In a 2009 e-mail, Hasan asked Awlaki whether "indiscriminately killing civilians" was allowed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Both e-mails were forwarded to the Defense Criminal Investigative Services (DCIS).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] However, DCIS failed to connect the two e-mails to each other, and the 2008 e-mail was given only a cursory investigation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] A DCIS agent later explained that the subject was "politically sensitive".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] In November 2013, Army Secretary John M.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] McHugh is quoted as writing that he has "directed my staff to conduct a thorough review of the record of trial in the court-martial of Major Hasan to ascertain if those proceedings revealed new evidence or information that establishes clearly the necessary link to international terrorism".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] A lawsuit filed in November 2011 by victims and their family members alleges that the government's failure to take action against Hasan before the attack was willful negligence prompted by "political correctness".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The 83 claimants sought $750 million in compensation from the Army.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] As of 2012, the Department of Defense classifies the case as one of workplace violence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] A group of 160 victims and family members have asked the government to declare the Fort Hood attack an act of terrorism, which would mean that injuries would be treated as if the victims were in a combat zone, providing them more benefits.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] On November 5, 2012, 148 plaintiffs, including victims and families of victims, filed a wrongful death claim against the United States Government, Hasan, and the estate of Anwar al-Awlaki.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Their lawsuit alleges there were due process violations, intentional misrepresentation, assault and battery, gross negligence, and civil conspiracy.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] The lawsuit was featured on ABC's *Nightline* on February 12, 2013.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] Later that year, the case was placed on hold pending the conclusion of Hasan's court martial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2009-fort-hood-shooting-p02] District Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly dismissed the wrongful death lawsuit for lack of jurisdiction, because the U.S. government was not named as a defendant.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 20, 2012, a mass shooting occurred inside a Century 16 movie theater in Aurora, Colorado, United States, during a midnight screening of the film *The Dark Knight Rises*.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 24-year-old James Eagan Holmes set off tear gas grenades and shot into the audience with multiple firearms.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Twelve people were fatally shot and 70 others were injured, 58 of them due to gunfire.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was arrested minutes later in his car outside the cinema.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Earlier, he had rigged his apartment with homemade explosives and incendiary devices.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] These were defused by the Arapahoe County Sheriff's Office Bomb Squad a day after the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Fearing copycat crimes, movie theaters showing the same film across the United States increased their security.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Gun sales increased in Colorado, and political debates were generated about gun control in the United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes confessed to the shooting but pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Arapahoe County prosecutors sought the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 16 of that year, Holmes was convicted of 24 counts of first-degree murder, 140 counts of attempted first-degree murder, and one count of possessing explosives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 7, the jury deadlocked on whether to impose the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 26, Holmes was given 12 life sentences, one for every person he killed; he also received 3,318 years for the attempted murders of those he wounded and for rigging his apartment with explosives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The shooting occurred in Theater 9 at the Century 16 multiplex (operated by Cinemark Theatres), located in the Town Center at Aurora shopping mall at 14300 E.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Police said that Holmes bought a ticket, entered the theater, and sat in the front row.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] About 20 minutes into the film, he left theater 9 through an emergency exit door beside the movie screen, with direct access to the lightly used parking area at the back of the complex, while propping the door slightly open with a plastic tablecloth holder.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There were about 400 people inside theater 9.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes went to his car (which he had parked near the exit door), changed into protective clothing, and retrieved his guns.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] About 30 minutes into the movie, police say, around 12:30 a.m., he reentered the theater through the exit door.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was dressed in black and wore a gas mask, a load-bearing vest, a ballistic helmet, bullet-resistant leggings, a bullet-resistant throat protector, a groin protector, and tactical gloves.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He was listening to a techno radio station, which was playing the song "*Becoming Insane*" by Infected Mushroom, through a set of headphones so that he could not hear anything from people in the theater.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Initially, few in the audience considered Holmes to be a threat.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some witnesses thought he was wearing a costume, like other audience members who had dressed up for the screening.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some believed he was playing a prank, while others thought he was part of a special effects setup for the film's premiere, or a publicity stunt by the studio or theater management.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes reportedly threw one canister towards the left side of the theatre, emitting a gas or smoke, that partially obscured the audience members' vision, made their throats and skin itch, and caused eye irritation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He fired a 12-gauge Remington 870 Express Tactical shotgun, first at the ceiling and then at the audience.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also fired a Smith & Wesson M&P15 semi-automatic rifle with a 100-round drum magazine, which eventually malfunctioned.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Finally, he fired a .40-caliber Glock 22 Gen4 handgun.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He shot first to the back of the room, and then toward people in the aisles.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A bullet passed through the wall and hit three people in adjacent theater 8, which was screening the same film.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Witnesses said the multiplex's fire alarm system began sounding soon after the attack began, and staff told people in Theater 8 to evacuate.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes fired 76 shots in the theater: 6 from the shotgun, 65 from the semi-automatic rifle, and 5 from the .40-caliber handgun.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The first phone calls to emergency services via 9-1-1 were made around midnight, prior to his attack, as can be heard in the opening statements of the prosecution, as well as the recorded transcript of his interview with the FBI.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At 12:39 a.m., after he began shooting, other victims began to call the police who arrived within 90 seconds and found three .40-caliber handgun magazines, a shotgun, and a large drum magazine on the floor of the theater.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some people reported the shooting via Twitter or text messaging rather than calling the police; officers were already at the theater by the time that the tweets were sent.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ambulances were hindered by chaos and congestion in the parking lot, and they were unable to reach the back of the complex where police had pulled the injured out through the emergency exit doors of Theatre 9.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Stephen Redfearn, one of the first police officers to arrive on the scene, sent victims to area hospitals in squad cars.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At about 12:45 a.m., police officer Jason Oviatt apprehended Holmes behind the cinema, next to his car, without resistance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Because of his tactical clothing, Holmes was at first mistaken for another police officer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He was described as being calm and "disconnected" during his arrest.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two federal officials said that Holmes had dyed his hair red and called himself "The Joker", although authorities later declined to confirm this.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Three days later, at his first court appearance in Centennial, Colorado, Holmes's hair appeared reddish-orange.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Later, the Colorado district attorney who prosecuted Holmes said he never called himself The Joker, and blamed the federal officials for the rumor.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The officers found several firearms in the theater and inside the shooter's car, including another Glock 22 handgun.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was found carrying a first-aid kit and spike strips, which he later admitted in an interview he had planned to use if police either shot at or chased him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Following his arrest, Holmes was initially jailed at the Arapahoe County Detention Center, under suicide watch.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The police interviewed more than 200 witnesses of the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Speaking on behalf of himself and FBI agent James Yacone, who was in charge of the investigation, Aurora Police Chief Dan Oates said he was confident that the shooter acted alone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] When apprehended, Holmes told the police that he had booby-trapped his apartment with explosive devices.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Police evacuated five buildings surrounding his Aurora residence, which was about 5 mi (8 km) north of the cinema.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes' apartment complex is limited to University of Colorado Medical Center students, patients, and employees.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One day after the shooting, officials disarmed an explosive device that was wired to the apartment's front door, allowing a remote-controlled robot to enter and disable other explosives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The apartment held more than 30 homemade grenades, wired to a control box in the kitchen and filled with at least 30 US gal (110 L) of gasoline.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Neighbors reported loud music from the apartment around midnight on the night of the massacre, and one went to his door to tell him she was calling the police; she said the door seemed to be unlocked, but she chose not to open it.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A police official said a Batman mask was found in the apartment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 23, police finished collecting evidence from the apartment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two days later, residents were allowed to return to the four surrounding buildings, and six days later, residents were allowed to move back into the formerly booby-trapped building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Twelve fatalities were reported along with 70 injuries.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 58 were hit by bullets, and were reported by mainstream news as the most victims of any mass shooting in United States history.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This figure was not surpassed until the 2016 Orlando nightclub shooting, which killed 49 people and injured 58 others for a combined total of 107 casualties.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Four people's eyes were irritated by the tear gas grenades, while eight others sustained non-gunshot injuries while fleeing the theater.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The massacre was the deadliest shooting in Colorado since the Columbine High School massacre on April 20, 1999.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ten victims died at the scene and two more were pronounced dead in local hospitals.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ghawi had survived the Eaton Centre shooting in Toronto that occurred a month prior.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The injured were treated at Children's Hospital Colorado, Denver Health Medical Center, The Medical Center of Aurora, Parker Adventist Hospital, Rose Medical Center, Swedish Hospital, and University Hospital.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 25, three of the five hospitals treating victims announced they would limit medical bills or forgive them entirely.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ashley Moser, Veronica Moser-Sullivan's mother, suffered critical injuries after being shot three times in the chest, neck, and abdomen.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] She was rendered a paraplegic due to one of the bullets lodging in her spine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Caleb Medley, the last victim discharged, left University Hospital on September 12.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He had serious brain damage and an injury to his right eye from a shotgun blast to the head and underwent three brain surgeries.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He required a feeding tube, had severely impaired movement, and could no longer speak.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Stefan Moton was paralyzed from the chest down after a bullet went through his spine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The Community First Foundation collected more than $5 million for a fund for victims and their families.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In September, victims and their families received surveys asking about their preferences for how collected funds should be distributed, either by dividing it equally among victims or through a needs-assessment process.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On November 16, 2012, the Aurora Victim Relief Fund announced that each family of the dead would receive $220,000.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes' booking photo was released, and he first appeared in court on July 23, 2012.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to press reports, he seemed dazed and largely unaware of his surroundings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 30, Colorado prosecutors filed formal charges against Holmes, including 24 counts of first-degree murder, 116 counts of attempted first-degree murder and one count of illegal possession of explosives.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two charges were filed for each victim to expand the opportunities for prosecutors to obtain convictions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Colorado State District Court Judge William B.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Sylvester, who was the trial judge overseeing the case, placed a gag order on lawyers and law enforcement, sealing the court file and barring the University of Colorado from releasing public records relating to Holmes' year at the school.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Media organizations challenged the sealing of the court file.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 9, Holmes' attorneys said he is mentally ill and they needed more time to assess the nature of his illness.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The disclosure was made at a court hearing in Centennial, Colorado, where news media organizations asked a judge to unseal court documents in the case.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors alleged on August 24, 2012, that Holmes told a classmate he wanted to kill people four months before the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A judge ruled on August 30 that a notebook written by Holmes, in which he allegedly described a violent attack, was covered by physician–patient privilege because it was addressed to his psychiatrist.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This made it inadmissible as evidence unless Holmes' mental health became an issue in the case.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors dropped their request for access to the notebook on September 20, 2012.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On January 2, 2013, prosecutors and defense attorneys in the case returned to court in advance of the preliminary hearing, the public's first officially sanctioned look at the evidence, due to the gag order.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors offered their case as to why the trial should proceed, and defense lawyers argued that it should not.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At the conclusion, Judge Sylvester decided there was enough relevant, admissible evidence to proceed to a trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Also on January 7, lawyers for both sides argued whether to admit four unspecified prescription bottles and immunization records investigators had seized from Holmes' apartment when they searched it in July 2012, considering doctor-patient confidentiality laws.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The judge ruled in October that prosecutors could keep the items.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On March 27, Holmes' lawyers offered a guilty plea in exchange for prosecutors not seeking the death penalty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On April 1, the prosecution announced it had declined the offer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Jury selection started on January 20, 2015.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On February 27, 2014, Arapahoe County District Court Judge Carlos Samour set the start of Holmes' trial for October 14.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The trial was delayed to December 8 upon a defense request for a continuance to further evaluate Holmes' mental condition.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On that date, the trial was again postponed, as Holmes' lawyers asked for another continuance to further prepare their case and review the paperwork of evidence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Jury selection eventually started on January 20, 2015, after a request by Holmes' lawyers for yet another continuance was denied.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The juror selection process lasted three months and summoned 9,000 candidates, making it the largest jury summons in U.S. history.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On April 15, selection ended, with a total of nineteen women and five men serving.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There were concerns about the selection of the jurors, as at least two from the pool of twelve primary jurors, along with twelve alternates, had ties to the 1999 Columbine High School massacre: "Juror No.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 535", was the aunt of a Columbine survivor; and "Juror No.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 737", was a student there at the time and was also a former friend of the shooters.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The trial began on April 27 with opening arguments by the prosecution explaining that Holmes intentionally went to the movie theater that evening with the deliberate intent to kill as many people as possible in a mass shooting spree.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The defense opened their argument by admitting the fact that Holmes was the shooter, but said that he was mentally ill with severe schizophrenia and was never in control of his right mind.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Starting on April 28, and over the next few weeks, prosecution testimony included various survivors of the massacre and enumerated the after-effects on the survivors.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 26, the notebook Holmes mailed to his psychiatrist hours prior to the shooting was presented as evidence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There had previously been intense debate as to whether the notebook was eligible as evidence and should be admitted, since it detailed Holmes' thoughts.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors argued the content in Holmes' notebook, which had attack plans, proved the shooting was premeditated, while Holmes' attorneys argued that his writing indicated his mental illness.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 27, William Reid, a court-appointed psychiatrist who interviewed Holmes for a total of about 22 hours, testified that Holmes was mentally ill but legally sane.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He diagnosed him as having schizotypal personality disorder, which is characterized by constricted behavior and difficulties relating to others.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Reid and another doctor evaluated Holmes in December 2013, determining him to be legally sane, and said that his mental illness did not prevent him from forming intent and knowing the consequences of his actions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes had told Reid that he did not target children, hence why he chose a PG-13 film showing, and felt remorse when he learned children were killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes's attorneys tried to call for a mistrial, saying that the jurors heard an unprompted opinion that complicated the legal standard for judging the sanity of a person, but the judge refused to grant the request.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 29, videos of Reid's interviews with Holmes in 2013 were shown to the court.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In the videos, Holmes described his social awkwardness and the violent, paranoid thoughts he had been having prior to the massacre.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also stated his belief that he was being followed by federal agents at the time of the massacre and hoped they would apprehend him at the theater before he could act.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to him, he transitioned from suicidal thoughts to homicidal thoughts after becoming depressed from his breakup with his girlfriend.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 8, a second psychiatrist, Jeffrey Metzner, testified that Holmes was mentally ill but legally sane when he plotted and carried out the shooting, and that he suffered from schizoaffective disorder.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He interviewed Holmes for a total of 25 hours.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 9, the trial came to a standstill after three jurors were dismissed by the judge for violating orders to refrain from talking about news reports regarding the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One of the jurors had begun discussions about sensitive details of the case with the other two jurors outside of the court on at least two occasions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two days later, Holmes's attorneys requested the dismissal of a fourth juror after her brother-in-law was shot during a robbery the previous day, and other jurors had seen her crying.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Judge Carlos Samour responded that he would consider it, and agreed to the motion by dismissing her on June 15.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 17, a fifth juror was dismissed after Judge Samour was advised that she personally knew a wounded victim of the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 19, the prosecution called as their last witness Ashley Moser, the mother of slain victim Veronica Moser-Sullivan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Moser was critically injured and left paralyzed by the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 9, Samour asked Holmes if he would testify in court, and advised him of his right to do so.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 10, the defense showed two videos of Holmes' behavior in his jail cell.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One video showed him running and slamming his head against the wall before sitting down while the other showed him tethered to a bed while naked, attempting to cover his head with a blanket and then a sheet.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 14, closing statements were made; jury deliberations began on July 15 and continued into July 16.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 16, after deliberating for over twelve hours, the jurors found Holmes guilty on all twenty-four counts of first-degree murder, 140 counts of attempted first-degree murder, one count of possessing explosives, and a sentence enhancement of a crime of violence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] They began deciding his sentence on July 22.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The court expected the sentencing phase to last for one month.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes declined to make an allocution statement.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 23, the jury ruled that Holmes acted in a cruel manner, was lying in wait, and ambushed his victims during the shooting, which constituted aggravating factors.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The jurors decided that Holmes did not intend to kill children when he opened fire.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 27, Holmes's sister testified that her brother became withdrawn from the family after they moved from Salinas to San Diego during his early teenage years.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 28, Holmes' father pleaded for his son's life, stating that he is severely mentally ill and did not deserve to die, regardless of his crimes.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He displayed photos of camping trips and family vacations with Holmes to the jury.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 30, Holmes' lawyers made a final appeal to the jurors, urging them to consider mental illness in his sentencing, despite their rejection of the insanity defense used in the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The appeal for clemency was rejected on August 3, based on mitigating factors such as mental illness not outweighing aggravating factors such as the number of casualties in the massacre.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 7, Holmes was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole after jurors failed to unanimously agree on a death sentence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One juror was opposed to sentencing Holmes to death due to his mental health issues, while two other jurors were uncertain.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Formal sentencing began on August 24 and ended on August 26.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 26, Samour formally sentenced Holmes to 12 consecutive life sentences without the possibility of parole for the murder charges, and an additional 3,318 years for the attempted murder and explosives possession charges.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The evening after the shooting, a candlelight vigil was held at the site in Aurora.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] President Barack Obama ordered flags at government buildings flown at half-staff, in tribute to the victims, until July 25.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Both Obama's and Mitt Romney's campaigns temporarily suspended television advertising in Colorado for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 22, President Obama met with victims and local and state officials and gave a nationally televised speech from Aurora.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Many world leaders sent their condolences, including Queen Elizabeth II, French President François Hollande, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Russian President Vladimir Putin, and Pope Benedict XVI.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 's reaction to the theater shooting in Aurora, Colorado.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros., the distributor of *The Dark Knight Rises*, said it was deeply saddened by the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The studio canceled the film's gala premieres in France, Mexico, and Japan, scaled down its marketing campaign in Finland, and decided not to report box-office figures for the movie until July 23.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some television advertisements for the film were also canceled.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Other major film studios joined Warner Bros. in withholding early box-office numbers on July 21.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros. reportedly made a "substantial" donation to Colorado's Community First Foundation to benefit victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Christopher Nolan, the film's director, spoke on behalf of his cast and crew and called the event "savage" and "devastating".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Christian Bale, who plays Batman in the film series, privately visited victims on July 24.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Members of the Colorado Rockies baseball team also visited victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Members of the Denver Broncos also called or visited individuals at the hospitals.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros. instructed cinemas to stop screening a trailer for the film *Gangster Squad*, which preceded *The Dark Knight Rises* screenings in some cities (though not in Aurora), because it contained a scene involving the main characters shooting at a movie theater audience with machine guns.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The film's release date was rescheduled to January 2013, and the theater scene was replaced by a new sequence in a different setting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In the wake of the shooting, DC Comics delayed the release of *Batman Incorporated* #3, which includes a scene in which a female Leviathan agent brandishes a handgun in a classroom full of children while disguised as a schoolteacher.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Animation reportedly edited the Cartoon Network series *Beware the Batman* to make the firearms look less realistic.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Hans Zimmer, who composed the soundtrack for *The Dark Knight Rises*, recorded a choral song entitled "Aurora" in honor of the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The song was sold for donations that went to a fund for the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark agreed to pay any funeral expenses incurred by the deceased victims' families not covered by the Crime Victims' Compensation Fund.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark closed the entire Century Aurora 16 multiplex in the wake of the shooting but reopened January 17, 2013, with a 40-minute ceremony led by Aurora Mayor Steve Hogan, followed by a showing of *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] As of 2020, Cinemark Theatres has not released any photographs or video evidence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Soon after the shooting, police departments and cinemas across the United States and around the world increased security for fear of copycat incidents.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In New York City, police officers were deployed to theaters screening the new film.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The National Association of Theatre Owners distributed checklists from the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Department of Homeland Security to its members and said in a July 21 statement that members were "working closely with local law enforcement agencies and reviewing security procedures".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] AMC Theatres announced it would "not allow any guests into our theatres in costumes that make other guests feel uncomfortable and we will not permit face-covering masks or fake weapons inside our buildings".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Three victims sued Cinemark Theatres in the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] District Court for the District of Colorado on September 21, 2012, for the company's alleged negligence in failing to provide adequate safety and security measures.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In response, Cinemark's representation filed a motion to dismiss on September 27, 2012, on the grounds that there was no liability under Colorado law for failure to prevent an unforeseeable criminal act.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark's motion quoted extensively from the landmark California appellate opinion that held McDonald's had no duty of care to prevent the 1984 San Ysidro McDonald's massacre.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On October 30, 2012, the court hearing the criminal case against Holmes denied a motion by some of the survivors that would have let them access sealed evidence for review in their civil action against the theater chain.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Magistrate Judge Michael Hegarty issued a recommendation that most of the claims be dismissed, as they were not allowable under Colorado law.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also said claims alleging violations of the Colorado Premises Liability Act could proceed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Brooke Jackson stated that for theaters today, "One might reasonably believe that a mass shooting incident in a theater was likely enough (that is, not just a possibility) to be a foreseeable next step in the history of such acts by deranged individuals".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Attorney Christina Habas, who represents several theater victims, has said, "We essentially don't have a single photograph, a single piece of evidence that we can show to a jury".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In June 2016, a federal judge dismissed the last claims in the lawsuit.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In a separate lawsuit in state court, Cinemark was sued by families of the victims, who alleged the theater should have taken greater measures to prevent such a shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In May 2016, after years of legal debate, a jury took three hours to deliver a unanimous verdict that the theater chain was not liable to any degree.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The judge allowed Cinemark Theatres to submit a bill of costs to the plaintiffs to recover expenses due to the litigation, as Colorado state law allows for prevailing parties.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In September 2016, Cinemark dropped all claims for reimbursement of legal fees.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On January 14, 2013, Chantel Blunk, the estranged wife and widow of victim Jonathan Blunk, sued the University of Colorado in federal court.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] She alleged that a school psychiatrist could have prevented the slaughter by having Holmes detained after he admitted he "fantasized about killing a lot of people".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This type of lawsuit had been anticipated in an August 2012 article co-authored by bioethicist Arthur Caplan which discussed the applicability of the landmark California Supreme Court decision in *Tarasoff v.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Regents of the University of California* (1976) to the facts of the Aurora shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A grassroots community center, Aurora Strong Resilience Center, was established by community leaders, elected officials, and mental health professionals, as a response to the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The center offers therapy for people who experienced traumatic stress from the theater shooting, and also people who were victims of other crimes and refugees who experienced a traumatic event in their country of origin before coming to the United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Colorado gun sales spiked after the shooting, with the number of background checks for people seeking to purchase a firearm in the state increasing to 2,887, up 43% from the previous week.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Gun sales in Washington, Florida, California, and Georgia also increased.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The shooting reignited the political debate on gun control, with one issue being the "easy access" Holmes had two semi-automatic rifles and high-capacity magazines, which were banned federally from 1994 to 2004.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The results of a survey released on July 30, 2012, by the Pew Research Center suggested the incident did not change Americans' views on the issue.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On March 20, 2013, Colorado governor John Hickenlooper signed House bill 13-1224, which made the sale, transferal, or possession of magazines holding 15 rounds or more illegal unless said magazines were lawfully owned prior to July 1, 2013.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The law also specified that firearms with a tubular magazine which are either chambered in .22 rimfire or operated by lever action are exempt from this regulation, as are magazines "permanently altered" to limit the capacity to 15 or fewer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 6, 2026, the United States Department of Justice sued the state of Colorado over the 2013 law banning high-capacity magazines, alleging it violates the Second Amendment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In 2015, a campaign titled "No Notoriety" was started by the parents of Alexander Teves, who died in the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to Teves' father, the campaign's incentive is to encourage media outlets to limit the usage of the suspect's name and photos when reporting about the Aurora shooting, as well as other mass shootings that receive national media coverage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In an interview on CNN, Teves' parents said they and the relatives of other victims believe the mass media coverage of Holmes' name and photo may inspire others to commit mass shootings for notoriety.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The Century 16 theater where the shooting occurred was rebranded as the Century Aurora theater by its parent company Cinemark Theatres.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Despite heavy criticism from families and loved ones of victims, the theater was not demolished and reopened to the public after cleaning and renovation on January 25, 2013, 6 months after the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The reopening ceremony, which was boycotted by opponents of the theater's reopening, included a memorial service and a screening of *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Theater room nine, where the actual shooting occurred, was combined with an adjoining room into a new XD theater room.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A memorial to the victims of the attack was installed near Aurora Municipal Center, some 850 m (929.57 yd) from the theater, and dedicated on July 19, 2018, one day before the sixth anniversary of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] It consists of a park-like dell with 83 abstract birds, one for each victim.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Thirteen of the birds, with translucent wings, are on a center column and represent the thirteen deceased victims, including the unborn child.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The memorial, titled "Ascentiate", was designed by artist Douwe Blumberg.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 2, 2015, an Islamic terrorist attack, consisting of a mass shooting and an attempted bombing, occurred at the Inland Regional Center in San Bernardino, California, United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The perpetrators, Syed Rizwan Farook and Tashfeen Malik, a married couple living in the city of Redlands, targeted a San Bernardino County Department of Public Health training event and Christmas party of about 80 employees in a rented banquet room.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Fourteen people were killed and 22 others were seriously injured.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook was a Muslim and an American-born citizen of Pakistani descent, who worked as a health department employee.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Malik was a Muslim and Pakistani-born green card holder.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] After the shooting, the couple fled in a rented Ford Expedition SUV.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Four hours later, police pursued their vehicle and killed them in a shootout, which also left two officers injured.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to the FBI's investigation, the perpetrators were "homegrown violent extremists" inspired by foreign terrorist groups.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They were not directed by such groups and were not part of any terrorist cell or network.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] FBI investigators have said that Farook and Malik had become radicalized over several years prior to the attack, consuming "poison on the internet" and expressing a commitment to jihadism and martyrdom in private messages to each other.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook and Malik had traveled to Saudi Arabia in the years before the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The couple had amassed a large stockpile of weapons, ammunition, and bomb-making equipment in their home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Enrique Marquez Jr., a friend and former neighbor of Farook's, was investigated in connection with his purchase of the two rifles used in the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marquez was arrested in December 2015, and later pleaded guilty to federal charges of providing material support for terrorism and making false statements in connection with the acquisition of a firearm.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marquez also admitted that, in 2011, he conspired with Farook to carry out shooting and bombing attacks, plans which were abandoned at the time.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Three other people, including Farook's brother and sister-in-law, were arrested for immigration fraud in connection with a sham marriage between Marquez and Mariya Chernykh (the sister-in-law of Farook's brother).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The attack was the deadliest mass shooting in the U.S. since the 2012 Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting and the deadliest terrorist attack to occur in the U.S. since the September 11 attacks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] It was surpassed by the Orlando nightclub shooting in June 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The attack remains the deadliest mass shooting in California since the 1984 San Ysidro McDonald's massacre.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook and Malik left their six-month-old daughter with Farook's mother at their Redlands home the morning of the attack, saying they were going to a doctor's appointment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook, a health inspector for the San Bernardino County Department of Public Health, attended a departmental event at the banquet room of the Inland Regional Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The event began as a semi-annual all-staff meeting and training event, and was in the process of transitioning into a department holiday party/luncheon when the shooting began.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] There were a total of 91 invited guests, with 75–80 people stated to have been in attendance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook arrived at the departmental event at about 8:30 a.m. and left midway through it at around 10:30 a.m., leaving a backpack atop a table.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Coworkers reported that Farook had been quiet for the duration of the event, and that he had been looking at his phone before his departure.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He posed for photos with other coworkers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Shortly before 11:00 a.m., the event went on an unscheduled break due to a technical problem.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] PST, Farook and Malik, armed with semi-automatic pistols and rifles, opened fire outside the building, killing two people.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook entered the building a minute later, firing on those in attendance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They wore ski masks and black tactical gear (including load bearing vests holding magazines and ammunition), but not ballistic or bulletproof vests.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The entire shooting took two or three minutes, during which the shooters fired more than 100 bullets before fleeing.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] During the shooting, many of those in attendance managed to escape the room and flee deeper into the building, while those who remained hid underneath tables or in bathrooms, closets, and cupboards.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] A bullet hit a fire sprinkler pipe, causing water to pour down the banquet room, making it difficult to see.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The perpetrators moved between tables, shooting anyone who moved or made a sound.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] One person was struck by a bullet that tore through an interior wall, while another was shot while trying to escape through a glass door near where the shooters had entered.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Three men attempted to stop one of the shooters, but all were shot; it was unclear if any of them survived.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] One victim was killed while shielding a coworker with his body.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Some initially mistook the attack as an active shooter drill; as some previous active shooter drills had taken place in the same banquet room.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] An unidentified source told an NPR journalist that witnesses appeared to recognize Farook by his voice and build.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Other witnesses easily identified one of the shooters as a female because of her slight build and tight-fitting clothes.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Sources reported that Malik pledged *bay'ah* (allegiance) to Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, the leader of Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), on a Facebook account associated with her as the attack was underway.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Later reports described the posting as being made on behalf of both shooters.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The perpetrators left three explosive devices connected to one another at the Inland Regional Center, contained inside the backpack left by Farook during the departmental event.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The devices were described as pipe bombs constructed with Christmas lights and tied together, combined with a remote controlled car that was switched on.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The poorly constructed devices failed to explode.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Authorities believe that the pipe bombs were meant to target the emergency personnel responding to the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The device was hidden inside a canvas bag, and its build was similar to schematics published in al Qaeda's *Inspire* magazine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Coworkers noticed the bag before the attack occurred, but thought that Farook would return for it and therefore did not investigate it.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] It took 3 minutes and 32 seconds for the first police unit to respond to the shooting following the initial 9-1-1 emergency call.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Two police officers with the San Bernardino Police Department (SBPD) arrived almost simultaneously at 11:04 a.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] When two other SBPD officers arrived two minutes later, the four officers entered the building through the southeast side and began to search for shooters.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Another team of four officers (one from SBPD and the others from the Fontana Police Department) entered the building from the northern side and joined the first team in clearing all of the first-floor rooms.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] At 11:14 a.m., the San Bernardino Fire Department made a Twitter post (or Tweet) about an emergency on the 1300 block of Waterman Avenue, with the police working to clear the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Roads in the area were closed to traffic.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The San Bernardino SWAT team happened to be conducting its monthly training exercise a few miles away from the scene at the time of the attack, which allowed them to arrive at the scene within eleven minutes.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Police used a battering ram to get into the complex.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The first floor was cleared by 11:17 a.m., and a secondary sweep of the building began fourteen minutes later.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As officers searched for shooters inside the building, others aided the wounded.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Probation officers initially set up a makeshift triage center near the entrance of the building, but deemed it to be too close and relocated it across the street by 11:15 a.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Because survivors were soaked from water pouring from the fire sprinkler pipe, they became slippery for officers to hold.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Injured victims were carried out on blankets and chairs, as litters and tactical stretchers were unavailable at the time.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] An SBPD tactical medic supervised the extraction operation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] It took 57 minutes to get the last of the injured to a hospital.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Ultimately, about 300 officers and agents from city, county, state, and federal agencies responded to the active-shooter event, converging on the scene as people were being evacuated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI, the ATF, and the Los Angeles Police Department counter-terrorism unit were called in to assist.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Police were on the lookout for a black SUV used by the perpetrators to flee the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] At 5:08 p.m., the explosive devices placed by Farook were discovered by an FBI SWAT officer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They were later detonated individually by a bomb squad, with the last detonation occurring at 8:37 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Earlier, at 11:33 a.m., an abandoned roller luggage bag was found in a second-floor office and mistaken for a suspicious device, but was deemed safe by 2:22 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The Inland Regional Center was declared clear by authorities at 9:29 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Law enforcement began a search for the suspects.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] A witness gave Farook's name to police, who quickly learned that he had rented a black Ford Expedition EL SUV with Utah license plates four days before the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Based on information provided by one of Farook's neighbors, two plainclothes investigators went to the perpetrators' Redlands home on North Center Street for surveillance shortly before 3:00 p.m., about four hours after the initial attack at the Inland Regional Center had begun.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They spotted Farook's vehicle leaving the residence and gave chase onto the freeway at 3:08:19 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Officers from other agencies joined the pursuit shortly afterward.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] At least one fake explosive‍—‌a metal pipe stuffed with cloth made to resemble a pipe bomb‍—‌was thrown at the police during the pursuit.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The SUV exited the freeway onto North Tippecanoe Avenue and briefly stopped at a stoplight, where a pursuing officer observed the perpetrators putting on tactical vests and equipping themselves with rifles.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The SUV then continued onward onto East San Bernardino Avenue and entered a suburban area, where the shooter in the backseat, identified as Malik, began firing at police through the back window at 3:08:43 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Eventually, at 3:09:22 p.m., the SUV stopped in a neighborhood about 1.7 miles (2.7 km) away from the scene of the initial attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The couple continued to exchange fire with police from inside their vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Malik opened the side passenger door and shot at the first police vehicle, which was about 210 feet (64 m) away from the SUV.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook exited the driver's front door, stood between the two open doors, and opened fire on the same vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As more officers converged, Farook walked across the street towards some homes while continuing to fire, pinning officers behind their squad cars.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He intended to flank the sheriff's deputy who had first stopped.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Realizing this, several officers repositioned themselves and focused their gunfire on Farook.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] One police officer eventually shot Farook in the right side, allowing others to flank and shoot at him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook fell to the ground, shot several times in the legs and upper body.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He fired at the police once with a handgun as he lay wounded on the ground, injuring an officer before the gun malfunctioned.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook was shot again several times and killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] His body was handcuffed and positioned to lie face-down afterwards.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Officers then fired on the SUV as Malik continued to shoot at them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] During this exchange of gunfire, a second police officer was wounded.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Using a police cruiser as cover, officers fired into the back of the SUV while rescuing the wounded officer and a second one.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] At 3:14:53 p.m., Malik was killed by several bullets that struck her in the body and head.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The gunfire lasted for around five minutes before both perpetrators were killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Police used BearCat armored personnel carriers in confronting the shooters.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Because authorities feared that the vehicle could contain explosives, the "Rook"—a motorized battering ram with a protective shield—was used to investigate the SUV.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The sheriff's department confirmed that a man and a woman were killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Seven police agencies were involved in the final shootout, with 23 officers firing a combined total of at least 440 rounds.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The perpetrators fired at least 81 rounds.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] During the shootout, police asked residents to stay indoors.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Nearly 2,500 rounds of .223-caliber and 9mm ammunition were recovered from the vehicle, along with medical supplies and a trigger apparatus believed to be for the explosives left behind at the Inland Regional Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Farook was struck 25 times, Malik was struck 15 times.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In the Inland Regional Center attack, 14 civilians were killed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Nine were residents of San Bernardino County, five from nearby Riverside, Los Angeles, and Orange counties.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Three (Isaac Amanios, Bennetta Betbadal, and Tin Nguyen‍) were refugees from Eritrea, Iran, and Vietnam, respectively.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Thirteen were county employees; ten were environmental health inspectors, comprising about a quarter of that department's workforce.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to autopsy reports released on May 27, 2016, all died from multiple gunshot wounds, mostly to their backs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Shannon Johnson and Bennetta Betbadal later died at a makeshift triage center across the street from the Inland Regional Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The attack injured 22 civilians, some seriously.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Several were hospitalized about 15 minutes after leaving the building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Five went to nearby Loma Linda University Medical Center and six to Arrowhead Regional Medical Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The last discharged was from Loma Linda on March 3, 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] One police officer was shot during the gunfight, and one was injured by flying glass or shrapnel.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Both were struck in the thigh; one realized he was hit thirteen hours later.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] After the attack, police identified married couple Syed Rizwan Farook and Tashfeen Malik as the perpetrators.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They used two illegally transferred .223-caliber semi-automatic rifles which had been modified to defeat California's magazine release requirements, two 9 mm caliber semi-automatic pistols, and an improvised explosive device in the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Neither shooter had a criminal record, and neither was on Terrorist Screening Database lists.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 3, 2015, the FBI took over as the leading federal law enforcement agency on the case, treating the probe as a counter-terrorism investigation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI conducted a "massive" investigation, and by December 7, 2015, had already conducted about 400 interviews and collected about 320 pieces of evidence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On January 5, 2016, the FBI began investigating what the perpetrators' activities were during an 18-minute period from 12:59 p.m. to 1:17 p.m. on the day of the shooting, and they appealed to the public for assistance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Investigators believe that the two were driving around the city in an apparent attempt to remotely detonate the explosive device they left behind at the scene of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The investigation found that the perpetrators were inspired by Islamic terrorists and Islamic terrorist organizations.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In Senate Judiciary Committee testimony given on December 9, 2015, FBI Director James B.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Comey said that they "were talking to each other about jihad and martyrdom," before their engagement and as early as the end of 2013.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] They reportedly spent at least a year preparing for the attack, including taking target practice and making plans to take care of their child and Farook's mother.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Comey has said that although the investigation has shown that the couple was radicalized and possibly inspired by foreign terrorist organizations, there is no indication that they were directed by such a group or part of a broader cell or network.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In one Arabic-language online radio broadcast, ISIL described the perpetrators as "supporters" following the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] During the police investigation into the attack, *The New York Times* reported that this language indicated "a less direct connection" between the shooters and the terrorist group.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In a December 5, 2015, English-language broadcast on its Bayan radio station, ISIL referred to the couple as "soldiers of the caliphate", which is a phrase ISIL uses to denote members of the terrorist organization.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] *The New York Times* reported that it was unclear why the two versions differed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 1, 2016, nearly one year after the attack, authorities speculated on Farook's forced participation in the training event and Christmas party as the trigger.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Newly discovered emails indicated that Malik had objected to the party and did not want her husband to participate.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] San Bernardino Police Chief Jarrod Burguan said in an interview with ABC News that Malik stated that "she didn't think that a Muslim should have to participate in a non-Muslim holiday or event" in an online account.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] After the deaths of the perpetrators, the focus shifted to a small townhouse in Redlands, a few miles away from San Bernardino; the place where Farook and Malik met after the shooting and where they lived.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] PST on December 2, 2015, police were executing a search warrant on the house.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to the San Bernardino police chief, Farook and Malik were listed in the rental agreement.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Investigators found 2,000 9-mm handgun rounds, 2,500 .223-caliber rounds, and the tools that could be used to make improvised explosive devices.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI also initially reported that it had removed twelve pipe bombs from the perpetrators' home; the FBI clarified several days later that it had recovered 19 types of pipes that could be converted into bombs from the home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) was able to complete an "urgent trace" on the firearms less than two hours after the guns were recovered.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The couple was not completely successful in destroying their personal electronics, including mobile phones and hard drives, prior to the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Pursuant to a federal search warrant, the authorities also searched a townhouse in Corona twice, where Farook's brother and father lived.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI said that the family was cooperating and authorities did not arrest anyone.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 10, 2015, federal authorities began searching Seccombe Lake park in downtown San Bernardino after receiving a tip that the shooters visited the area on the day of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] A dive team was sent into the shallow edge of the lake to search for evidence; nothing relevant was found.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] After the FBI completed a search of the perpetrators' townhouse, it was turned over to its landlord.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 4, 2015, the landlord used a crowbar to open the door to the home and allowed reporters and photographers to "swarm" the home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] NBC News correspondent Kerry Sanders said that *Inside Edition* paid the building's landlord US$1,000 to access the home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] MSNBC, CNN, and Fox News all broadcast live video from the home, showing images of personal photographs, documents, identification cards, and baby items.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The scene was described as having a "media circus" atmosphere.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Sanders, in particular, was criticized for showing close-up images of children's photographs and Farook's mother's identification card; the network later said it regretted doing so.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to legal experts, the broadcast was not illegal, but it raised concerns about journalistic ethics.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On February 9, 2016, the FBI announced that it was unable to unlock one of the mobile phones they had recovered because of the phone's advanced security features.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The phone was an iPhone 5C owned by the county and issued to its employee, the shooter Farook.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI first asked the National Security Agency to break into the phone, but the NSA was unable to do so.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As a result, the FBI asked Apple Inc. to create a new version of the phone's iOS operating system that could be installed and run in the phone's random access memory to disable certain security features.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Apple declined due to its policy to never undermine the security features of its products.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI responded by successfully applying to a United States magistrate judge, Sherri Pym, to issue a court order, mandating Apple to create and provide the requested software.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The order was not a subpoena, but rather was issued under the All Writs Act of 1789.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Apple announced their intent to oppose the order, citing the security risks that the creation of a backdoor would pose towards its customers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] It also stated that no government had ever asked for similar access.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The company was given until February 26, 2016, to fully respond to the court order.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In response to the opposition, on February 19, 2016, the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Department of Justice filed a new application urging a federal judge to compel Apple to comply with the order.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The new application stated that the company could install the malware on the phone in its own premises, and after the FBI had hacked the phone via remote connection, Apple could remove and destroy the malware.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The same day, Apple revealed that it had discussed with the FBI four methods to access data in the iPhone in early January, but one of the more promising methods was ruled out by a mistake during the investigation of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] After the shooter's phone had been recovered, the FBI asked San Bernardino County, the owner of the phone, to reset the password to the shooter's iCloud account in order to acquire data from the iCloud backup.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] However, this rendered the phone unable to back up recent data to iCloud unless its passcode is entered.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] This was confirmed by the Department of Justice, which then added that any backup would have been "insufficient" because they would not have been able to recover enough information from it.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The San Bernardino County District Attorney, Michael Ramos, filed a brief claiming the iPhone may contain evidence of a possible third shooter and a "dormant cyber pathogen" that could have been introduced into the San Bernardino County computer network.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On March 28, the Department of Justice announced that it had unlocked the iPhone and withdrew its suit.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Initial reports, citing anonymous sources, stated that Israeli company Cellebrite was assisting the FBI with this alternative.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] However, *The Washington Post*, citing anonymous sources, reported that the FBI instead paid "professional hackers" who used a zero-day vulnerability in the iPhone's software to bypass its ten-try limitation, and did not need Cellebrite's assistance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In April 2021, *The Washington Post* reported that the Australian company Azimuth Security, a white hat hacking firm, had been the one to help the FBI.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In September 2016, the Associated Press, Vice Media, and Gannett (the owner of *USA Today*) filed a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) lawsuit against the FBI, seeking to compel the agency to reveal who it hired to unlock Farook's iPhone, and how much was paid.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On September 30, 2017, a federal court ruled against the media organizations and granted summary judgment in the government's favor.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] National reactions to Apple's opposition of the order were mixed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] A CBS News poll that sampled 1,022 Americans found that 50% of the respondents supported the FBI's stance, while 45% supported Apple's stance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Initial news reports and witness accounts following the attack led to a search for up to three shooters, but police eventually determined that there were only two since only two firearms were used in the attack according to ballistics evidence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Immediately following the shootout that killed the perpetrators, investigators in armored vehicles at the perpetrators' townhouse considered ordering an evacuation, but instead ordered the neighborhood to shelter in place and cordoned off the area.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] From 4:00 p.m. to 5:30 p.m., police asked residents of the area to stay in their homes with doors locked and secure after residents reported a person jumping fences.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] No one was found; the reports may have been from officers at the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] A person detained after running away from the scene of the shootout was thought to be a possible third suspect, but police determined that he was not connected to the shooting; the person was booked on an unrelated outstanding misdemeanor warrant.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On February 18, 2016, the FBI revealed that they have not ruled out the possibility of a third shooter, but clarified that they are continuing to operate under the assumption that only two shooters were involved.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Some witnesses who claimed to have seen three gunmen at the Inland Regional Center continued to assert their accounts.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As of December 1, 2016, it was reported that the FBI had yet to rule out that possibility.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Enrique Marquez Jr., a next-door neighbor of Farook's until May 2015, and who is related to him by an immigration fraud sham marriage, was investigated in connection with his purchase of the two rifles used in the attack, a charge to which he agreed to plead guilty.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] There is no record of a transfer of the weapons from Marquez to the attackers.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Though not regularly, Marquez attended both the Islamic Center of Riverside and the Islamic Society of Corona-Norco four or five years before the attack, and stood out because of his Hispanic background.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Federal prosecutors allege that in 2011, Farook and Marquez conspired to carry out shooting and bombing attacks at the library or cafeteria at Riverside Community College, where both were students, and on rush-hour traffic on California State Route 91 in Corona.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marquez reportedly told authorities that he and Farook tried to carry out the attack in 2011 or 2012.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] This plan was abandoned after three men in the Inland Empire were arrested for their plan to kill Americans in Afghanistan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Though the FBI had previously disputed this fact, Marquez was found to have ties to these men in 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] By 2011, Marquez spent most of his time in Farook's home, listening to, watching, and reading radical Islamist propaganda, including *Inspire* magazine, the official publication of Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP), and videos produced by Al-Shabaab as well as the sermons of Anwar al-Awlaki.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On November 29, 2014, Marquez entered into a sham marriage with Mariya Chernykh, a Russian woman who arrived in the U.S. on a J-1 visa and the sister of the wife of Farook's older brother.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to *The New York Times*, Marquez was said to have been paid between $5,000 and $10,000 to enter the green card marriage so that Chernykh could become a U.S. citizen.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Early on December 5, 2015, federal authorities searched Marquez's Riverside home under a federal search warrant.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He waived his *Miranda* rights and cooperated "extensively" with federal investigators, "discussing at length his relationship with" Farook.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On December 17, 2015, Marquez was arrested and charged in the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] District Court for the Central District of California with three federal criminal counts: conspiracy to provide material support for terrorism (i.e., himself, a firearm, and explosives); making a false statement in connection with acquisition of firearms ("straw purchase"); and immigration fraud.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Another "straw purchase"-related charge and another immigration fraud charge were added on December 30, 2015.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He faced a maximum of 50 years in prison if convicted on all of the charges.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The court ordered Marquez held without bail, saying that Marquez would pose a danger to the community if released.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marquez initially pleaded not guilty to all of the charges against him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On April 28, 2016, he was named in an indictment as a co-conspirator in document fraud in relation to the arrest of Mariya Chernynk.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In February 2017, as part of a plea agreement with federal prosecutors, Marquez pleaded guilty to conspiracy to provide material support to terrorists and to making false statements in connection with the purchase of a firearm.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marquez also admitted to plotting with Farook the alleged abandoned terror plots in 2011.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As part of the plea agreement, the government agreed to dismiss the marriage fraud charges.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The maximum sentence is 25 years in prison plus a $500,000 fine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Testifying in court when Marquez's guilty plea was entered, the father of one of the victims denounced the plea agreement, saying that it would lead to a sentence that was too light; the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Attorney explained that while he understood the father's pain, the government did not have enough sufficient evidence to prosecute Marquez for more serious offenses.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The sentencing hearing was initially set for November 6, 2017, but it was postponed to February 26, 2018, four days before.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Sentencing was postponed indefinitely on June 26, 2018, after Marquez obtained a new attorney.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On October 23, 2020, Marquez was sentenced to 20 years in prison.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Navy in the Iraq War from 2003 to 2007, and was awarded two medals for service during the war on terror.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] He was described by friends and neighbors as sociable and extroverted compared with his brother Rizwan.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In 2011, he married Tatiana, a Russian citizen who immigrated to the U.S. in 2003 from her home village of Vysokiy, located 400 miles (640 km) from Moscow.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Tatiana had first settled into Richmond, Virginia, immediately after arriving into the U.S. on a J-1 visa.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] There, she married another man, but the couple divorced in 2010 and Tatiana moved to southern California, where she met Raheel.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In California, she began launching several businesses, including a kiosk in The Shops at Montebello, a shopping mall.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Mariya Chernykh, the younger sister of Tatiana Farook and also from the village of Vysokiy, left Russia and entered the U.S. on a J-1 visa in July 2009 and failed to depart on October 30 of the same year as required by her visa.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] At some point since her arrival in the U.S., she made an application for asylum, though it is currently unknown if it was ruled on.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] She dated a Los Angeles man for years and had a child with him, but were forced to split up due to the sham marriage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On November 29, 2014, Chernykh entered into a sham marriage with Marquez in order to gain legal status in the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] According to *The Los Angeles Times*, after the sham marriage, Chernykh struggled to play her part; on Christmas 2014, she was urged by Tatiana to stop posting online photos of herself with her ex-boyfriend.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] She began working with her sister as a saleswoman at her sister's kiosk.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In January 2017, she pled guilty to immigration fraud.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In late 2015, Chernykh and Marquez were set to be interviewed by immigration officials.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] As a result, according to the indictment, Raheel Farook created a fraudulent back-dated lease agreement that claimed the two were living with him and his wife since their marriage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Raheel and Tatiana Farook also allegedly staged family photos of Chernykh and Marquez, and established a joint transaction account for them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Prosecutors allege that on December 3, the day after the Inland Regional Center attack, Tatiana Farook lied to investigators about Chernykh and Marquez's marriage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On February 18, 2016, the FBI searched a residence belonging to Raheel Farook, but did not comment on the exact nature of the search.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Raheel was not arrested or named a suspect at that time.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] On April 28, 2016, the Farooks and Chernykh were arrested and charged with conspiracy to knowingly make false statements under oath with respect to immigration documents.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] These charges carry a maximum sentence of five years.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] All three pleaded not guilty to the charges against them in a federal court in Riverside.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Raheel Farook's mother and Chernykh's ex-boyfriend agreed to post their bails.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The day following her arrest, Chernykh posted her bail, but she was transferred to the custody of the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Immigration and Customs Enforcement by the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Marshals Service and is being held at Adelanto Detention Center.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Deportation proceedings against her are pending, but are on hold until the criminal case is resolved.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Attorney Eileen Decker issued a statement, saying that the charges arose from the investigation into the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The indictment alleged that Chernykh paid Marquez to enter into a sham marriage to obtain U.S. immigration benefits.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Chernykh pleaded guilty to conspiracy, perjury, and two counts of making false statements.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] While she faced up to 20 years in prison, on May 17, 2021, she was sentenced to three years probation, serving no jail time, and her Russian passport was returned to her by the court.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In January 2017, Raheel Farook pleaded guilty to one felony count of conspiracy to commit immigration fraud, arising from his making of a false statement in support of Chernykh's application for permanent residency.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The following month, Tatiana Farook pleaded guilty to the same crime.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The maximum sentence in both cases is five years in prison, three years of supervised release, and a $250,000 fine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Both were initially set to be sentenced on November 13, 2017, but this was postponed to March 19, 2018, three days before.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Both were later sentenced to three years of probation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] In March 2020, Rafia Sultana Shareef, the mother of Syed Rizwan Farook and Syed Raheel Farook, pleaded guilty to one count of destroying evidence, becoming the only person prosecuted for a crime directly related to the December 2015 terrorist attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Attorney Julius Nam argued, "The defendant chose to deliberately destroy a document that was central to the understanding of the planning".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] The FBI recovered what prosecutors called the "attack plan" from a shredder in Raheel Farook's home in Corona and reconstructed it using a computer and scanner, according to Assistant U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] It also listed action items such as practicing at a shooting range, destroying electronics that authorities could use for tracking, purchasing parts to construct IEDs, and transferring funds to Shareef's bank account.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] Bernal sentenced Shareef to six months of home confinement and three years of probation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p01] While the maximum sentence had been 20 years in federal prison, under her plea agreement she faced at most 18 months in custody.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On March 18, 2016, California State Assemblyman Freddie Rodriguez of the Joint Legislative Committee on Emergency Management conducted a hearing in which first responders were to share details of the response to the attack and possible aspects that could be improved on.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] During the hearing, Michael Madden, a lieutenant with the San Bernardino Police Department and one of the first responders to respond to the Inland Regional Center, requested state aid in encrypting police radio channels.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] He explained that police communications were playing out real-time across the U.S. during the attack, being broadcast on YouTube and other network systems.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] According to Madden, this put first responders at risk, as potential suspects could have been monitoring the communications and tracking the actions of law enforcement.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] He added that the City of San Bernardino, as well as San Bernardino County, were moving towards a radio system that will incorporate encrypted frequencies.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] President Barack Obama called for "common sense" gun safety laws and stronger background checks as part of a bipartisan effort to reduce the frequency of such shootings.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In an interview with CBS News' Norah O'Donnell, Obama said, "We have a pattern now of mass shootings in this country that has no parallel anywhere else in the world." Obama called for legislation to block people on the anti-terrorism No Fly List from purchasing weapons.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Speaker of the House Paul Ryan opposed this proposal, saying that denying persons on the list the right to bear arms would violate their due process rights.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On January 8, 2016, Representative Pete Aguilar of Redlands spoke on the floor of the House of Representatives and called for gun control.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] After the shooting, gun sales in California increased by more than 18,000, following an overall down year for statewide sales.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Applications for concealed carry permits also rose 750 percent in San Bernardino County.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The families of the shooting victims reacted to President Obama's executive action to tighten gun regulation and expand background checks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] A number of family members expressed support for the plans as necessary and long overdue, while a few doubted whether they would reduce gun violence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Prior to the attack, a measure was sponsored by Senator Dianne Feinstein; it would allow the U.S. to ban sales of guns and explosives to people listed on government watch lists of suspected terrorists.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The so-called "Feinstein Amendment" came to the Senate floor one day after the attack, but failed on a party-line vote, with Democrats in favor and Republicans opposed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On June 16, 2016, Tina Meins, the daughter of one of the fourteen people killed in the attack, spoke in a press conference arranged by Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy, just a day after Murphy launched a fifteen-hour filibuster on the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Senate floor, regarding federal gun control legislation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In the press conference, Meins asserted her support for gun control and questioned the Senate's vote against the Feinstein Amendment, explaining that more than 2,000 terror suspects were able to purchase firearms since 2004.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The measures have been opposed by a number of politicians and gun rights organizations such as the National Rifle Association and Gun Owners of California.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Some of the bills were approved by Governor Brown on July 1, 2016, and went into effect in 2017.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On January 13, 2016, the wife of one of the slain victims filed wrongful death claims against San Bernardino County and dozens of unidentified individuals, and also sought damages totaling $58 million, saying that her husband's death was preventable and caused by negligence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On January 22, 2016, three relatives of another slain victim filed identical claims against the county for similar reasons and also claimed that the county fostered a hostile workplace environment and failed to provide safety to the Inland Regional Center's employees.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The three relatives sought for a total of $204 million.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] At least five San Bernardino city residents filed claims with the City of San Bernardino seeking reimbursement for least $12,000 in property damage caused by bullets in the shootout, which hit a resident's truck and other items; the city council voted 5–2 to deny the claims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The city police were one of seven law enforcement agencies on the scene, and it is uncertain which agency fired what bullets.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On May 31, 2016, federal prosecutors filed a lawsuit against Farook's family.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] This lawsuit would allow them to seize both the proceeds of two life insurance policies (and the policies themselves) held by Farook, both of which listed Farook's mother as the beneficiary.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] One policy worth $25,000 was taken out by Farook in 2012 when he started working for the county, while the other, worth $250,000, was taken out the following year.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] According to NBC News, "Under federal law, assets derived from terrorism are subject to forfeiture.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On September 2, 2016, government officials said they wanted to give the money to the victims' families.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In December 2022, *The Press-Enterprise* reported the insurance company had paid the claims, but the money was being held by the court pending resolution of the case.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On May 5, 2016, a group created by San Bernardino County announced plans for a memorial dedicated to the victims and survivors of the attack, as well as the first responders involved.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Details about the design of the memorial, meant to be a fountain and garden, were released on the next day.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Groundbreaking was slated to begin on June 2, the six-month anniversary of the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] As of 2017, however, the memorial was still in the development stage.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Such memorials usually take five to ten years to be completed.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Hours after the attack, classes were canceled at California State University, San Bernardino and at Loma Linda University following a bomb threat that was called in to the university's medical center, where many injured victims were being treated.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On December 15, after the Los Angeles Unified School District received a threat of attack by "explosive devices" and other means, Superintendent of Schools Ramon Cortines ordered the closure of all schools in the district for the day.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Cortines cited the San Bernardino incident as an influence in his decision to close the schools.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] New York City received the same threat, but the New York City Department of Education determined it was a hoax and took no action.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On September 9, 2016, the Police Foundation and the U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Department of Justice's Office of Community Oriented Policing Services (COPS Office) released a review of law enforcement response to the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On the one-year anniversary of the attack, it was reported that a number of survivors were accusing San Bernardino County of cutting off support for them.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On the first anniversary of the attack, a bicycle ride hosted by the Redlands-based club "Ride Yourself Fit" was held at 7:30 a.m.; dozens of local bicyclists, many of them police officers, rode 14 miles (23 km), with one mile representing each person killed in the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The remembrance bicycle ride continues to be held every December 2.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] A remembrance ceremony was held at a local blood bank at 8:00 a.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Later that morning, over 200 people at the Inland Regional Center held a moment of silence outside the building.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] At 3:30 p.m., a "Peace Garden" was opened on the campus of California State University, San Bernardino; it was dedicated in the memory of five of the victims, who were all alumni of the university.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Following the attack, county offices, including the Department of Public Health, were closed the remainder of the week, with only the most essential services remaining open.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Most of the county's 20,000 employees returned to work on December 7, 2015, though Inland Regional Center personnel worked remotely.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The Inland Regional Center remained closed until January 4, 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Its two main buildings now operated under heightened security; the building where the attack took place will remain closed indefinitely.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The location of a planned train station next to the center was moved eastward due in part to the center's new security procedures.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The City of San Bernardino incurred up to US$1 million in unforeseen expenses (such as the deployment of more police officers on extended shifts) as a result of the attack, and planned to seek state and federal emergency funds to help cover the costs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] California governor Jerry Brown declared a state of emergency in San Bernardino County, since roughly 35 percent of the Department of Public Health employees were among those killed or wounded in the attack, and the attack left the county with very few health inspectors to do critical work.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The emergency declaration will allow the state of California to send in additional health inspectors for assistance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On March 22, 2016, San Bernardino County unanimously voted to accept a US$1.5 million agreement with the California Association of Environmental Health Administrators to provide up to 30 temporary health inspectors to replace those currently on leave.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] As of May 29, 2016, 50 percent of county environmental health staff remain on leave, and temporary staff remain on loan from Riverside, Orange, Los Angeles, Contra Costa, Marin, Ventura, and San Luis Obispo Counties.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] About 2,000 local residents gathered at a candlelight vigil at San Manuel Stadium in downtown San Bernardino the day after the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Carey Davis praised the first responders, said that the tragedy "has forever impacted our community," and talked about how the community had come together following the attack.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Five of the victims and one of the killers were graduates of California State University, San Bernardino; on December 8, 2015, more than 1,000 students, alumni, and community members attended a candlelight vigil on campus in honor of the victims.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On January 4, 2016, a memorial for the slain victims was held at the Citizens Business Bank Arena in nearby Ontario, with thousands in attendance, including Governor Brown, California Attorney General Kamala Harris, former New York City mayor Rudy Giuliani, and Christian pastor Rick Warren.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] After the attack, a relief fund for San Bernardino was set up and has raised US$2.48 million as of March 3, 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On July 5, 2016, the relief fund finished distributing the entirety of its raised money to the families of the deceased victims (which all received 80 percent of the funds), the 22 people injured (who received 15.5 percent), and witnesses to the shooting (who received 4.5 percent).
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] There were 75 named recipients in total, though the two police officers injured in the shootout with the perpetrators declined their share of the compensation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] President Barack Obama ordered U.S. flags to be flown at half-staff at the White House, public buildings, military installations, Navy ships, embassies, and diplomatic missions.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On December 18, 2015, President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama met in San Bernardino with families of the fatal victims, and emergency personnel who first responded to the incident.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The governors of several states also ordered flags to be lowered to half-staff in their states as well.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In California, the annual Christmas tree lighting ceremony at the State Capitol was canceled and all flags were lowered to half-staff.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Twelve of the dead were members of the Service Employees International Union; SEIU international president Mary Kay Henry said, "Our hearts are broken from this tragedy. ...
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] American Muslim organizations, including Council on American–Islamic Relations (CAIR) and Islamic Society of Orange County, condemned the attacks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] A night vigil was held the day after the attacks at the largest mosque in the San Bernardino County, the Ahmadiyya Baitul Hameed Mosque.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In the aftermath of the shooting, CAIR reported an escalation in anti-Muslim hate crimes in the U.S., including the throwing of a pig's head at a mosque in Philadelphia, the beating of a Queens shop owner, and incidents of death threats and vandalism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] A number of attacks and incidents of vandalism in southern California in the weeks following the attack were investigated as anti-Muslim hate crimes.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] A "Muslims United for San Bernardino" campaign to raise money to assist victims' families with funeral expenses and other needs raised more than US$152,000 from more than 1,000 donors, becoming the most successful crowdfunding venture Muslim Americans have ever launched.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On January 19, 2016, *Dabiq*, the online propaganda magazine of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant, released an issue praising the shooting and the perpetrators.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In an address to the nation delivered from the Oval Office on December 6, 2015, President Obama declared the shooting an act of terrorism, referring to the shooters as having "gone down the dark path of radicalization" and embracing a "perverted version of Islam".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] It was just the third speech from the Oval Office in the seven years of Obama's presidency.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Many Republican U.S. presidential candidates at the time, among them Marco Rubio, Ted Cruz, and Donald Trump, responded by claiming the United States was at war.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Chris Christie, who was campaigning in Iowa at the time, declared, "What the fact is this is a new world war and one that won't look like the last two.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Some Muslim leaders objected to Obama's request that American Muslims help to "root out" extremism in their communities.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Palestinian-American activist Linda Sarsour commented, "I'm tired of this idea that extremism can only mean Muslims or Islam or people who are associated with Islam ... why is it that we're only obsessed with Islam and Muslim communities?".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] "We would never ask any other faith community to stand up and condemn acts of violence committed by people within their groups", she said.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] On June 18, 2016, President Obama issued a Weekly Address addressing the San Bernardino attack and a mass shooting that occurred at a gay nightclub six days earlier.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] In the speech, he addressed the topics of homegrown terrorism and gun control.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Trump's suggestion was met with condemnation from both Democratic and Republican candidates for the presidency in 2016.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Trump, in an interview on *Good Morning America*, cited the internment of Japanese Americans, German Americans, and Italian Americans during World War II as precedent for his proposal.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The attack reignited the debate over whether U.S. government should expand electronic surveillance of Americans, and specifically whether Congress should adopt legislation mandating that technology companies provide a backdoor so that law enforcement has access to encrypted communication.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Technology companies oppose such legislation, arguing that it would unacceptably undermine security.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] At a December 9, 2015, hearing before the Senate Judiciary Committee, FBI Director Comey called upon tech companies offering end-to-end encryption (such as Apple) to revise their "business model".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] There is no evidence that the shooters in San Bernardino used encrypted communications, although Comey said the attackers in the Curtis Culwell Center attack earlier the same year exchanged encrypted text messages.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Senators Richard Burr and Dianne Feinstein, the chairman and ranking member, respectively, of the Senate Intelligence Committee, are working on encryption legislation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] Additionally, Feinstein reintroduced legislation that would require tech companies to report "knowledge of any terrorist activity" they become aware of, a measure that worried Silicon Valley technology companies, which object to such measures on privacy grounds.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2015-san-bernardino-attack-p02] The use of BearCat armored vehicles by police during the shootout revived debate over use of military and military-style equipment by police, with some law-enforcement officials saying that the shooting showed a need for police to acquire such equipment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On March 22, 2021, a mass shooting occurred at a King Soopers supermarket in Boulder, Colorado, United States.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Ten people were killed, including a local on-duty police officer.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The shooter, 21-year-old Ahmad Al Aliwi Al-Issa, was arrested after being shot in the right leg.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He was temporarily hospitalized before being moved to the county jail.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] After undergoing mental evaluations during the legal proceedings, Al-Issa was found mentally incompetent to stand trial in December 2021 and in April 2022.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On August 23, 2023, prosecutors announced that Al-Issa was mentally competent to stand trial; a judge ruled as such on October 6 of that same year.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On September 23, 2024, Al-Issa was found guilty in the shooting and sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The shooting began shortly after 2:30 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] MDT (20:30 UTC) when a gunman entered the parking lot of a King Soopers supermarket and began to fire at people.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He was described by witnesses as wearing an "armored" vest and holding a "rifle", which turned out to be a semi-automatic Ruger AR-556 AR-15 style pistol that was used in the shooting; he also carried a 9mm semi-automatic handgun.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He was first seen by employees and customers who watched him shoot at customers in the parking lot before turning and entering the store.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At the time, there were at least 115 people inside the building and at least 25 others in the parking lot.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The first victim was a repairman who was killed in a van parked next to the gunman's vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The gunman then walked towards the store; along the way, he killed another person in the parking lot who was trying to flee, shooting him multiple times.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Next, he killed one more person while entering the store through its eastern entrance.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A man waiting in line with his family for his COVID-19 vaccine at the store's pharmacy witnessed the gunman shoot a woman at the front of the line before finding safety in a coat closet with his family.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Some customers and employees reached safety through a back exit for the supermarket.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Some were praised for their actions in helping evacuate and hide individuals away from the gunman.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At 2:33 p.m., the Boulder Police Department began receiving calls of a person with a "patrol rifle" in the area and shots being fired.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Witnesses at the scene reported hearing anywhere from 10 to 30 shots fired in rapid succession by the gunman.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Running towards gunfire, one of the officers, Eric Talley, was shot and killed by the gunman.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He was the last victim in the shooting, according to Boulder police.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Less than 30 seconds after Talley's death, additional officers entered the store.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] By 2:39 p.m., responding officers reported being fired upon repeatedly by the gunman.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At around the same time, an armored police vehicle was used to break the store's front windows.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Officers engaged the gunman in a shootout from 3 p.m. to 3:21 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] They also used a sound system to order him to surrender.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] According to police and witnesses, the gunman was laughing and occasionally mumbling.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A store employee said that while she was hiding, she heard gunshots and screams and then only the store music and phones ringing afterward.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Police did not enter the store again until 3:22 p.m., fearing an ambush.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] When a team of ten officers from multiple agencies reentered, they encountered the gunman at one of the aisles within 20 seconds of their entry; he fired at them at least twice.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] One of the officers returned fire on two different occasions, eventually striking the gunman in the thigh.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] I'm naked", and at 3:28 p.m., he was taken into custody using Talley's handcuffs.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He had a leg gunshot wound at the time of his arrest, so he was first transported to Boulder Community Health Foothills Hospital.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Police eventually transferred him to the Boulder County Jail, where he was held without bond.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The assailant discharged his rifle 47 times during the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] After the gunman was taken into custody, police searched through the store and evacuated people who had remained inside.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A shelter-in-place order was issued in the area at 4:18 p.m. and lifted at 6:40 p.m.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Up to 15 agencies responded to the shooting, including the Jefferson County SWAT, the Boulder Sheriff's Office, the University of Colorado Police Department, the FBI, the ATF, and local police departments.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A fire department ladder truck was used to get a SWAT team onto the roof.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At least three medical helicopters were summoned to a staging area at nearby Fairview High School.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Officer Talley, who had been working with the Boulder Police Department since 2010, was one of the first police officers to arrive at the scene.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] His death marked the first time a Boulder police officer was killed in the line of duty since 1994 and only the sixth such death in the department's history.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Seven of the victims died inside the store, while the other three died outside.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] While Boulder Police Chief Maris Herold initially said several other police officers were injured during the response, the department later said that no other officers were injured.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Aside from the suspect who was wounded by police, the only other injury from the shooting was a woman who fractured her back while trying to escape.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] According to a police affidavit, Al-Issa bought a semi-automatic Ruger AR-556 pistol.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Boulder police clarified in a news conference on March 26 that they believed the AR-556 pistol was the only weapon used by the suspect during the shooting and added that he also had a 9mm handgun with him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Al-Issa's identity was already known to the Federal Bureau of Investigation due to a link to another person under investigation by law enforcement officials.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Al-Issa expressed on Facebook and to his former high school wrestling teammates that he believed he was being targeted for harassment due to racism and Islamophobia.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] According to SITE Intelligence Group, "there was no indication on his Facebook account that suggested radical views of any kind, whether it be Islamist, anti-Trump, or anything else." Al-Issa's brother said he believed that the shootings were not a political statement.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The Boulder County District Attorney waited to reveal more information about Al-Issa's motives while the FBI and other agencies were investigating the case, to help ensure a fair trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At around 8 p.m. on the day of the shooting, a procession honored Officer Eric Talley as his body was being taken to a funeral home.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A separate memorial for the victims was created along a chain-link fence bordering the store, as mourners placed candles, flowers, and other items along its base or through the chain-link.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The Museum of Boulder began collecting and preserving stories and artifacts from the memorial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On April 16, it started planning both short-term and permanent memorials with the City of Boulder.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On May 12, the store was announced to be undergoing extensive renovations, with the expectation that it would reopen in late fall 2021.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Governor Jared Polis ordered the state's flags to fly at half-staff for ten days: one day for each victim.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] President Joe Biden also ordered flags on federal property nationwide to be flown at half-staff.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] This order came on the same day as the expiration of a federal order to fly flags at half-staff to honor the victims of the Atlanta spa shootings of March 16, less than a week before.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A week after the shooting, Talley's funeral was held; it included a 21-gun salute and another procession.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Sports teams in Colorado and victims of other mass shootings expressed sympathy for the victims and family members of the Boulder shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] A vigil for the victims and survivors of the shooting was held on March 25.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Representative Joe Neguse, whose district includes Boulder, spoke at the vigil about curbing gun violence.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] University of Colorado Boulder professor and poet Khadijah Queen also spoke at the vigil, which was organized by gun violence prevention group Moms Demand Action.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] In an interview with CNN's Anderson Cooper that day, the family of one of the victims spoke about him and their appreciation for the outpouring of support.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] As of June 29, more than $8 million in donations were collected by more than a dozen funds, primarily ones set up by Community Foundation Boulder County and the Colorado Healing Fund.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] However, victims' families criticized the organizations' distribution of the donations, saying that they were forced to produce bills and bank statements to receive support and that they were not given sufficient input into the money's distribution.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] They have since called for an independent audit into the distribution's methods.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The store remained closed for remodeling for almost a year.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] It was scheduled to reopen in January 2022, but the reopening was delayed due to a union strike until February 9.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The redesigned store, including a prominent mural at the entrance, was previewed to the media the evening before.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The reopening ceremony featured first responders and store employees.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Dignitaries included King Soopers president Joe Kelly, Mayor Aaron Brockett, and Polis, a Boulder resident.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] After the shooting, police investigated if Al-Issa used a 30-round magazine in the shooting, and also whether other firearms were connected to him.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] They found that he was equipped with ten high-capacity magazines, all of which were found on him, or in his car parked outside the store.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Subsequent to other mass shootings, possession of high-capacity magazines was banned in Colorado after 2013.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The Boulder District Attorney said that there was no evidence the magazines were sold or obtained illegally, but that Al-Issa broke laws by having them on his person and in his vehicle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] After the shooting, Al-Issa was charged with ten counts of first-degree murder and one count of attempted murder.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Al-Issa's identity was revealed to the public on March 23, the day after the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At Al-Issa's first court appearance on March 25, his lawyer asked for a mental health assessment.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] It was later reported that, due to "safety concerns and threats", Al-Issa was moved to another county.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On April 22, Al-Issa was charged with 43 new felony charges, including 32 counts of attempted murder, 10 counts of using a high-capacity magazine, and one count of first-degree assault.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The 32 counts of attempted murder include those of 11 police officers, along with a number of civilians.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On May 25, Al-Issa was charged with 13 additional counts of attempted murder and 47 "crime of violence sentence enhancers".
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] His next court appearance was a preliminary hearing scheduled for September 7.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] However, on September 1, Al-Issa's lawyers filed a motion to raise the issue of their client's mental competency during the trial, and the preliminary hearing was changed to an advisement hearing.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On September 7, Al-Issa was ordered to undergo a competency evaluation at the Boulder County Jail, to be completed within three weeks.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On September 28, the evaluation's due date was delayed to October 11, while a hearing to review the results was rescheduled for October 14.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On October 11, psychologists expressed their beliefs that Al-Issa was mentally incompetent to proceed with the trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On October 14, a judge granted the district attorney's request to have Al-Issa undergo a second evaluation.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The protracted process of determining Al-Issa's competency was criticized by the family of shooting victim Rikki Olds, who said Al-Issa was competent enough to plan and carry out the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On December 3, a judge ruled that Al-Issa was mentally incompetent to stand trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He has been held at Colorado Mental Health Institute since that month.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On April 15, 2022, a judge ruled that Al-Issa was still mentally incompetent to stand trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Six months later, on October 21, a judge ruled Al-Issa still incompetent for trial and set his next review hearing for January 27, 2023, when he was again deemed mentally incompetent for trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] In the meantime, the Colorado Mental Health Institute must provide monthly condition updates to the court.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Based on doctors' assessments, District Attorney Michael Dougherty expected the defendant's competency will improve, that he will be able to stand trial and justice will be served.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On August 23, 2023, prosecutors announced that Al-Issa was mentally competent to stand trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On October 6, 2023, a judge ruled that Al-Issa was mentally competent to stand trial.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On November 14, 2023, he pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity; his bond was set at $100 million.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The trial date was tentatively set for August 2024 with the jury selection scheduled to begin early that month.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On May 7, 2024, the trial was delayed to September 2, 2024.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Jury selection began on August 26, 2024, and opening statements were made on September 5.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] After a two-week trial, the jury deliberated on September 20 and 23 before finding Al-Issa guilty of 10 counts of first-degree murder, 38 counts of attempted murder, one count of first-degree assault and six counts of using a high-capacity magazine.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Later that day, he was sentenced to 10 consecutive life sentences without parole plus 1334 years.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Death penalty was not considered, since Colorado abolished it a year before the shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Al-Issa legally purchased a Ruger AR-556 pistol on March 16 at a local gun shop in Arvada that used Colorado's universal background check law, even though he was previously convicted of third-degree assault, a misdemeanor with a sentencing maximum of 18 months in county jail.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Federal firearms laws only prohibit weapons purchases for those convicted of a felony, or a misdemeanor with a prison term of over 24 months.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] He was reported to be carrying a 9 mm handgun in addition to his primary weapon.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] On March 12, four days before Al-Issa bought his Ruger AR-556 pistol and ten days before the shooting, a Boulder County judge had blocked a ban on the sale and possession of assault weapons and large capacity magazines.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The judge ruled in a lawsuit supported by the NRA Institute for Legislative Action (NRA-ILA) to strike down the ban.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] The ban had been passed in Boulder in 2018 after the Stoneman Douglas High School shooting.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Following the Boulder shooting, discussion was renewed on the topic of gun control.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Particular discussion was raised over the Ruger AR-556 pistol, a type of AR-15 style rifle with a modified arm brace, legally defined as a pistol and not a rifle according to gun control laws.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Semi-automatic AR-15-style rifles are modeled after the automatic ArmaLite AR-15 rifle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] As a pistol, the Ruger AR-556 is not bound by stricter regulations placed on rifles, and pistols usually aren't included in definitions of assault weapons.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] According to the federal Gun Control Act of 1968, a pistol is "designed to be gripped by one hand"; a rifle is a weapon designed "to be fired from the shoulder" with a single bullet fired for each pull of the trigger, among other criteria.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Similar to AR-15 style rifles, Ruger AR-556 magazines typically have a capacity of 30 rounds; but since Colorado law prohibits magazines carrying more than 15 rounds, some retailers sell a Colorado-specific version of the gun that comes with a magazine that holds under 15 rounds.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Mary's University's Criminal Justice Programs, said about the Ruger AR-556 pistol, "It's not a sporting rifle, it's not a hunting rifle.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] At the national level, President Joe Biden called for an immediate ban on assault weapons; other Democratic politicians echoed his sentiments, including U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Senator Dianne Feinstein of California, U.S.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Representative Joe Neguse of Colorado, and former President Barack Obama.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] Biden also urged that loopholes be closed in the background check system and praised Officer Eric Talley, who was killed in the shooting, for his heroism.
[src:2021-boulder-shooting/2021-boulder-shooting] In an interview with *CBS This Morning*, Vice President Kamala Harris responded to the mass shootings by discussing the need for gun reform legislation.
